<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Soldiers in Angola Expected Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean soldiers serving in
Angola are expected back home by December this year as the United
Nations winds its peacekeeping mission in the war torn southern
African country, the Zimbabwean Defence Minister said today.
</P>
<P>
''We are in the process of making arrangedments of pulling out
in compliance with the U.N. directive, and before the end of the
year we would have pulled outmost of our soldiers,'' Defence
Minister Moven Mahachi told the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
October 30 marks the end of the current mandate of the U.N.
observer mission in Angola with all the non-African countries
that formed part of the U.N. military contingent having already
pulled out.
</P>
<P>
Out of the U.N.military contingent which is under the command
of Zimbabwean Major-General Philip Sibanda, only Zimbabwe, Zambia
and Namibia are still to withdraw their forces.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.Angola Verification Mission with some 7,000 troops and
military observers, has been monitoring the implementation of a
1994 agreement signed in Zambia in 1994 which ended nearly two
decades of civil war between the Angolan government and the
former rebel National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Commending the Zimbabwean forces for their professionalism
while in Angola, Mahachi said, ''I am very impressed with their
performance as they have lived to the expectations of our people
who are disciplined and peace loving by their nature.''
</P>
<P>
Mahachi discounted the possibility of resumption of war in
Angola, saying its nationals probably now realised the
destructiveness of armed conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
