<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Urge Preparation for Treaty Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Luxembourg, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Justice and internal affairs
ministers from the 15 European Union (EU) countries agreed here
today that no lax period should be allowed before the
implementation of the Amsterdam Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The two-day informal conference, which opened in Luxembourg
today, has started to propose and discuss matters concerning the
implementation of the Amsterdam Treaty, which was signed on
October 2 in Amsterdam to replace and complement the former
Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The ministers today discussed the procedures which would
possibly follow in the next few months concerning the
implementation of the new treaty, saying that the period before
the implementation should also be "put into good use."
</P>
<P>
They said that they were unanimous in sending the right signal
to EU citizens that they did not want to see any lax period before
the new treaty formally went into effect.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, scheduled to discuss the issue of EU enlargement
Friday, also held talks today on combating cross-border organized
crimes, joint control on illegal immigration and police and
customs cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It was proposed at the conference that a working group should
be set up to make pragmatic preparations for the implementation of
the Amsterdam Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
