<HEADLINE> Remaining Assembling Camps in Angola to be Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Commission of the
Angolan Peace Process decided today to close all the assembling
camps in the country after all the UNITA soldiers have been
disbanded by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Angolan Minister of Assistance
and Social Reintegration Albino Malungo after the joint
commission met to discuss humanitarian assistance and the
disbandment of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He said the out of a total of 15 assembling camps in Angola,
12 have been closed. The remaining three assembling camps based
in central and southern Angola will also be closed after the
soldiers of the former rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) are all disbanded by October 31.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government official urged the UNITA soldiers in
the three camps to continue to stay there, waiting to be
disbanded.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the UNITA to stop its operations of moving
its soldiers in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Joint commission meeting was chaired by the United Nations
special envoy based in Angola, Blondin Beye, and attened by
representatives from the Angolan government, the UNITA and
observers the United States, Russia and Portugal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
