<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece to Hold Military Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot National Guard's
annual military exercise code-named "Nikiforos '97" will start
Friday, with the participation of Greek airforce and navy, a
high ranking military officer announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Demoetrios Fasaris, the National Guard's Chief of Staff, told
reporters that some 9,000 National Guard reservists will take
part in the manoeuvres.
</P>
<P>
He said the scenario includes National Guard's reaction after
an enemy's military pre-emptive strike, with the fall of
parachutists.
</P>
<P>
Greece's National Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopolulos is
expected to arrive in Cyprus Monday to watch the last part of
the five-day exercise, which will climax with a military parade,
according to Fasaris.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and the Greek defense
minister will take the salute of a military parade next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Cyprus and Greece signed a joint defense
pact in November 1993, under which the Greek armed forces will
provide Cyprus with assistance in case the island is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey, which
deploys 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
