<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Urges Moscow to Protect Safety of Non-CIS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has urged the Moscow authorities
to process some 15,000 asylum-seekers from outside the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) and to prevent them from
being harassed as illegal residents.
</P>
<P>
Despite considerable efforts made by the Russian Federal
Migration Service to implement an asylum procedure in some parts
of Russia, authorities in Moscow have been slow in accepting
asylum-applications, particularly from people who are not from
non-CIS citizens, UNHCR said in a press release issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The frustration of asylum-seekers flared into spontaneous
violence Monday, when some 50 asylum-seekers from Angola and
former Zaire stormed into a refugee reception center and
demolished the premises, according to UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
"We had been fearing that such an incident might happen," John
Horekens, UNHCR's director for Europe, said in a statement. "For
years, these people have been living with no prospect of a better
future, in conditions of great hardship, with no security or
rights. They are feeling increasingly hopeless and, in the face of
growing xenophobia, are turning desperate."
</P>
<P>
Monday's incident occurred when representatives of
asylum-seekers visited the reception center to request funeral
fees for a Zairean asylum-seeker who was allegedly killed last
Friday by two unidentified Russians in Mytishi, 20 kilometers
north of Moscow, UNHCR said.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,400 Angolans and former Zaireans are registered in
Moscow, together with 30,400 others from non-CIS countries. UNHCR
provides limited cash allowances as well as medical, school and
social services to 277 Angolans and former Zairean asylum-seekers
in Moscow area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
