<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Sign Agreement on Border Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany today
signed an agreement on border cooperation between their police and
customs authorities at an informal meeting here of justice and
internal affairs ministers from the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Internal Affairs Jean-Pierre Chevenement and
German State Secretary Kurt Schelter signed the agreement in
Mondorf in Luxembourg, where the EU ministers started the two-day
conference today.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement signals that the two countries
have taken a further step in their border cooperation which can be
dated back a long time ago, Chevenement said at a news briefing
after the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries are going to establish a
cooperation center in ensuring that their joint efforts to carry
out an effective border control can go smoothly. But the exact
siting has not yet been decided.
</P>
<P>
The German state secretary agreed that this was a further step
taken in the direction of bilateral border cooperation between
France and Germany, which has turned a sensitive issue because of
rampant organized cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached in the framework of the Schengen
Agreement which was signed in March 1995, aimed at opening up
borders to citizens of all EU member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Could Be Stronger Than German Mark: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The on-going fiscal consolidation
among European Union countries as well as the economic benefits to
be gained from their planned monetary union could eventually make
the single European currency, the euro, stronger than the German
mark, a leading economist said today in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
"There is little doubt in my mind that the euro will be just as
strong as the German mark.... In fact there is every reason to
believe that the euro will be even stronger than the mark," the
German news agency DPA quoted economist Marc Hendriks as telling
an economic conference in Berlin today.
</P>
<P>
Hendriks, managing director of economic research for the
European investment house SBC Warburg, also said he believed that
the single European currency was likely to pose an effective
challenge to the U.S. dollar. "After all, it is the first time
that the dollar has had any real competition," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also expressed the belief that it was only a
matter of timing that the British government would change its mind
to support the country's participation in the euro club. 
</P>
