<HEADLINE> Kirghiz President, Russian PM Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 9 (Xinhua) -- There are no differences between
Russia and Kirghizstan on political, economic and state issues,
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said in Bishkek,
capital of Kirghizstan, today, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said this after talking with Kirghiz President
Askar Akayev in Bishkek, where a meeting of the heads of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) governments was held, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Akayev expressed satisfaction with the bilateral relations,
saying that the two states created a firm legal foundation for
their relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted Kirghizstan was the only republic in the CIS this year
to receive a Russian state credit of 45 million U.S. dollars to be
channeled to support the republic's energy sector, including the
purchase of turbines, generators and spares.
</P>
<P>
The Kirghiz president especially noted that "industrial growth
in Russia is the most important factor for the economies of all
CIS countries," since Russian enterprises manufacture the main
production resources for them.
</P>
<P>
Akayev believed that an intergovernment commission on economic,
scientific and cultural cooperation will give an important impetus
to the development of bilateral relations and will start
implementing specific projects.
</P>
<P>
It was said that an agreement on creation of the
intergovernment commission is expected to be signed Friday as a
result of the intergovernment talks between the Russian and
Kirghiz delegations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the existing problems in bilateral relations,
Chernomyrdin voiced support for simplifying formalities to make
mutual trips by citizens of the two countries as well as for
lifting restrictions on cooperation between Russian and Kirghiz
firms.
</P>
<P>
Akayev meanwhile emphasized the importance of Russia as a
trading partner of his country, since the Russian Federation is
responsible for over 30 percent of the total volume of Kirghiz
foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
