<HEADLINE> 1st Int'l Meeting of Aerospace Medicine to Open in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The first international meeting
of aerospace medicine will open Friday in the northern Greek port
city of Thessaloniki to mark the launching of the first satellite
into space.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, which is organized by the newly
established Hellenic Aerospace Medicine Society, cosmonaut Valery
Polyakov of Russia and astronauts Millie Hughes-Fulford and Fred
Haise of the United States will give accounts of their experiences
in space.
</P>
<P>
As crew member of the Russian space station Mir, Polyakov holds
the longest record in space with spending 14 consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
Hughes-Fulford, a space bus crew member, has participated in
several voyages and has organized a number of medical studies on
diseases such as cancer and osteoporosis while Haise was a crew
member of the Appollo 13 space shuttle which traveled to the moon
in April 1970. 
</P>
