<HEADLINE> Russian Communists Insist on Raising No-Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Communist Party
intends to raise the question of no-confidence for the government
early next week, Gennady Zyuganov, the leader of the Russian
Communist Party, told a news conference in the State Duma today.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov said the Federation Council should discuss the
proposal of deputies of the lower house to hold "a round-table
conference" of representatives of three branches of the
authorities, trade unions and political forces. As is known, this
idea was advanced by Communists and their allies.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Communist Party has sent 89 telegrams to every
chief of a subject of the federation, requesting support for the
idea of a "round-table conference."
</P>
<P>
According to Zyuganov, if the Federation Council backs this
initiative, and trade unions have already supported it,
representatives of the three branches of power will be able to
discuss the law on land, the tax code, the military reform, and
this may serve as the basis of a normal course and acceptable
budget.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question what could compel Communists to give
up the idea of no-confidence for the government, Zyuganov said
that the president and the government have an opportunity to make
a decision before the meeting, and there are many variants of
decisions.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party leader is confident that the 1998 budget
will now be turned down and will be referred to a special
trilateral commission of representatives of the State Duma, the
Federation Council and the government.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov noted the Communists are "strongly against" the
conciliatory commission. 
