<HEADLINE> Israel to Further Release Palestinian Tax Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to push peace
process forward, Israel today informed the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) that it will release 170 million shekels (about 48
million U.S. dollars) of Palestinian tax revenues to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting between Israeli Deputy Finance Minister
Shmuel Lavin and PNA Planning and International Cooperation
Minister Nabil Sha'ath in West Jerusalem, Lavin confirmed that
the Israeli government intends to further return the tax revenues,
which have been held by Israel for several months.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have complained that because the tax
revenues was frozen by Israel after the July 30 twin suicide
bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, some PNA employees
could not get their salary in time.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Palestinian Finance Minister Mohammed Zuhdi
Nashashibi announced that although Israel had returned 40 percent
of the withheld tax money, there were still 110 million dollars of
Palestinian tax money in Israeli hands.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision to repay the owed money is considered as a
good gesture to the PNA after the resumption of the
long-deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace talks early this week
and the first meeting Wednesday in the past eight months between
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and PNA President Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and the PNA was stalled last
March when Israel started to build a controversial new Jewish
neighborhood in Arab East Jerusalem. The bombing attacks in
Jerusalem in July and September, which killed 25 people and
wounded more than 300 others, have deepened the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Due to peace efforts by the international community, both
sides made the hard decision to get peace process back on track
in a bid to ease the tensions and prevent the situation in the
region from exploding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
