<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Nigeria Reacts Slowly to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain seems in a hurry to lift
its ban on Nigeria-registered aircraft from its airspace enforced
this May and resume flights on the lucrative London-Lagos route.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the British High Commission to Nigeria said a
letter signed by British authorities concerned dated on August 14
was delivered to the Nigerian authorities on August 21.
</P>
<P>
The letter confirmed that "the UK aeronautical authorities are
lifting the ban on Nigerian-registered aircraft with immediate
effect."
</P>
<P>
About a month later, another letter reiterating that the UK
aviation authorities had actually lifted the ban was written by
the acting high commissioner to the Nigerian Ministry of Aviation
on September 19.
</P>
<P>
However, up to September 25, Nigerian Aviation Minister Ita
Udo-Imeh came out to deny having been aware of the decision.
</P>
<P>
The air commodore said reportedly if there was such a
development, his ministry would be the first to break the news.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Andy Stern, regional general manager of the
British Airways, re-confirmed here the unconditional lifting of
the ban, saying that his company was keen to resume the
London-Lagos route.
</P>
<P>
Still there has been no reaction from the Nigerian government
to date.
</P>
<P>
The ban, imposed by the British side on May 6 this year,
precluded all Nigerian airlines from plying the lucrative
Lagos-London route.
</P>
<P>
It cited the inability of Nigerian aviation authorities to
comply with safety oversight as stipulated by the International
Civil Aviation Organization as reason for the action, which
further accentuated the frosty relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Even before that, Nigeria's national carrier, the Nigeria
Airways was banned from flying to London since February because
of alleged frauds in its airplane insurance.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Nigeria's Ministry of Aviation asked the
British Airways to stop flying to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Now after some five months have passed with few news about
substantial improvement in the safety of the Nigerian civil
aviation sector, the British changed its attitude and has taken
the initiative to seek for resumption of air services.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the British Airways have reportedly kept making
inquiries on the normalization of flights between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We await his (the minister's) response and remain keen to
start flying again with our traditional good value for money,
fares and high quality services," said Andy Stern.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the British airline's haste is not difficult to
understand, according to observers here, because it has suffered
an estimated loss of more than 80 million U.S. Dollars for ticket
revenue alone since the impasse.
</P>
<P>
As for the alleged linger of the Nigerian aviation authorities
to react, observers believe there should be something more than
simply to resume flights on the mentioned route by both sides.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed Nigeria Airways senior official reportedly said
earlier this week that the lifting of the ban to reciprocate the
British gesture would only prepare the ground for renegotiations
of the Bilateral Air Services Agreement signed between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the British Airways is bound to recruit its
cabin crew for the Lagos-London route from Nigeria as has been
the airline's practice in other countries. However, the crew at
service now are non-Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Nigeria Airways has to use 350-seated DC10
aircraft to carry passengers while the British Airways employs
Boeing 747 that has a capacity for 450 passengers.
</P>
<P>
By this, the British airline is short-changing its Nigerian
counterpart by 100 passengers for every flight it makes on the
London-Lagos route.
</P>
<P>
It might be clear that doing business on the basis of equality
and mutual benefit should be what Nigeria is seeking to resolve
its dispute with Britain.
</P>
<P>
And for the Nigerians, there comes the opportunity to look
into the infringement of the accord by the British Airways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
