<HEADLINE> Mozambique Telecom Company Earns $4 Million Last </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- An annual report released here
today by Mozambique Telecommunications Corporation (TDM) said the
company earned 46.7 billion Meticais or 4 million U.S. Dollars
last year, an 84 percent increase over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report was read out at the ongoing international meeting
on Mozambique telecommunications here at the capital. According
to the report, TDM's total income for last year is 658.9 billion
Meticais (57 million Dollars), up 16 percent compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the increase to the 2 percent expansion
of nationwide telephone network, a 29.6 percent and 2.2 percent
growth in domestic and international call fees respectively.
</P>
<P>
Rui Fernandes, TDM's general manager said at the meeting that
the only choice for the company to cope with challenges from the
21st century and resist infiltrations from foreign companies into
the Mozambican market is to privatize it gradually.
</P>
<P>
The privatization plan for TDM, he noted, has been sent to the
country's ministerial meeting, which is expected to reach a final
decision on October 14.
</P>
<P>
TDM plans to form "strategic alliance" with international
corporations which could provide technology and capital it needs,
Fernandes said. He disclosed that TDM needs a total of 350
million Dollars of investment by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
TDM is the only telecom company in Mozambique, with 2,416
staff members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
