<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tsetse Flies in Zanzibar under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar has achieved
resounding success in wiping out the notorious tsetse flies with
the use of insect sterilization method.
</P>
<P>
A tsetse eradication team on the isles, led by Dr Arnold Dyck,
said today that the tripanosomiosis disease caused by tsetse
flies among animals is almost non-existent.
</P>
<P>
The success has been attributed to the effectiveness of the
sterile insect technique (SIT), an environmental friendly
technology in which male tsetse flies are reproduced and
sterilized by gama rays, rendering them unable to reproduce when
they mate with female flies, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
The reproduction and radiation of male tsetse flies are being
done at the Tanga-based tse-tse and Tripanosomiosis Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
Then the gama sterilized flies are packed ready for aerial
releases from aircraft, which have targeted on the primary tsetse
habitat areas in the southern half of Unguja Island, including
the Jozani Forest.
</P>
<P>
The project, aimed at completely wiping out all tsetse flies
on Unguja island through application of SIT aerial releases, were
introduced in August of 1994. Almost eight million sterile male
flies have been dispersed over Unguja Island since then.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar is the only place in the world where this method has
been experimented, Dyck said, adding that the success of the
model project has proved that it can be experimented anywhere in
the world.
</P>
<P>
He said research on disease incidence in sentinel animals
declined to a negligible level early this year.
</P>
<P>
The project has cost about one million U.S. Dollars annually
over the past four years. It has been mainly financed by the
Zanzibar government and the International Fund for Agricultural
Development (IFAD). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
