<HEADLINE> UN Official: Iraq Receives More Food Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has received 2.13 million
tonnes of foodstuffs and other supplies in line with the first
phase of the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal launched last December,
a U.N. official said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, spokesman of the U.N. humanitarian
affairs coordinator in Iraq Eric Valet said that shipments of
medicine worth 5.3 million U.S. dollars arrived in Iraq last week,
bringing the total sum spent on medicine by Iraq so far to over
47 million dollars, accounting for 22.4 percent of the 210 million
dollars earmarked for the health sector during the first phase.
</P>
<P>
International observers are now present at the Al Walid post
along the Iraqi-Syrian borders where another shipment of food
is due to arrive in Iraq, Valet said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the oil-for-food accord has made progress in
providing food to the Iraqi people during the first phase. The
U.N. is sparing no effort to implement the accord
"satisfactorily." Foodstuffs will continue to flow into Iraq, he
added.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the second phase of the oil-for-food deal which
started on June 8, Valet said that until October 6 the
U.N. Sanctions Committee had received 61 requests from the Iraqi
government for humanitarian supplies with 28 contracts having been
approved.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to export 2
billion dollars worth of oil over a six month period to buy food,
medicine and other basic needs for the Iraqi people suffering
under U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
