<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Has Lowest Business Costs: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada has the lowest business
costs among seven leading North American and European countries,
according to an international study by the professional services
firm KPMG.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is a clear winner" when the impacts of land purchase,
labor taxation and others are combined, said Stuart MacKay, KPMG
partner-in-charge of the study, which was released here today.
</P>
<P>
The study, covering seven countries in Europe and North
America, estimated the total cost to start up a new production
site and operate it for 10 years, for businesses in eight
industries.
</P>
<P>
It found that business costs were lowest in Canada, followed in
order by Sweden, Britain, the United States, Italy, France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the study was welcomed by Canada's
International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi.
</P>
<P>
"These results clearly show that, on the basis of cost, Canada
is the number one location for investors compared to the U.S. and
Europe," Marchi said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, each of the seven countries has its own particular
strengths in different areas.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Canada have the lowest initial investment
costs. Land costs in the U.S. is the lowest, while Canada has the
lowest construction costs.
</P>
<P>
Labor costs, including wages and benefits, are lowest in
Britain, followed by Canada.
</P>
<P>
Transportation costs to the North American and European
marketplace are lowest in Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has the lowest electricity costs, which was closely
followed by Canada.
</P>
<P>
And Canada boasts the lowest interest costs and corporate tax
burden.
</P>
<P>
The KPMG study was sponsored by the Royal Bank of Canada,
Canada's Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade and
Ontario Hydro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
