<HEADLINE> French Interest Rate Rise Not to Affect Economy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The raise of a key interest rate
by the French central bank, La Banque de France, will not affect
the economic policy of the French government, said French Minister
of Industry, Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn today.
</P>
<P>
The Banque de France today raised its tender rate from 3.10
percent to 3.30 percent, a few minutes after the German Bundesbank
made a similar readjustment.
</P>
<P>
The French central bank said that the decision is aimed at
"durably preserving in the present phase of economic cycle the
monetary stability and good level of confidence in the French
franc, and thus maintaining an appropriate environment for a
substantial, healthy and durable economic growth in the 1998-1999
period."
</P>
<P>
"That will not change our economic policy or our framing of
action which is not affected by this raise of 0.20 points of
basis," said Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
He said, "All the indices of today, the consumption of
families, the inquiry into industry, confirm that the economic
resumption is there, that it is solid and... general in
continental Europe."
</P>
<P>
He said that the French government aims to achieve a 3 percent
economic growth in 1998, and a short-term rise of banking interest
rates will only have a marginal impact on the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
