<HEADLINE> Drastic Action Demanded After Violence Causes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Authorities in Richmond in
South Africa's Kwazulu-Natal province today demanded drastic
measures, including house-to-house searches, to stop the new wave
of violence in the area, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Five more people were killed Wednesday night in two separate
raids on homes, adding the deaths rose to 13 since violence
resumed Saturday night after a period of relative peace in the
area.
</P>
<P>
At an emergency meeting, the Richmond council passed a
resolution calling for prompt and effective action by security
forces, including house-to-house searches.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations of the council will be brought to the army
on Friday, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the SANDF (South African National Defense Force)
should cordon off the area and conduct house-to-house searches
for weapons and criminals," Richmond Mayor Andrew Ragalavoo said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the community was in a state of panic following the
latest attacks and that there might be a flow of refugees from
there.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's incidents occurred in the Hlahla and Cuba areas
surrounding Richmond.
</P>
<P>
Many people were so terrified that they chose to sleep outside
rather than in their houses, although the cold snap and rains
made doing this unpleasant, said the mayor.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal Premier Ben Ngubane said Wednesday that he would
suggest to President Nelson Mandela that a state of emergency
seemed to be the only way to deal with the continuing conflict in
the area.
</P>
<P>
The Richmond area saw frequent clashes between supporters of
the ruling African National Congress (ANC) and the Zulu-based
Inkatha Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
All the people killed Wednesday appeared to be from
ANC-supporting areas, police spokesman Henry Budhram said.
</P>
<P>
He said in both attacks the men, armed with R4 and R5 rifles,
appeared to be searching for particular people.
</P>
<P>
The ANC today condemned the new killings. "The precision and
regularity with which these killings are carried out can only
imply support from forces that have both financial and material
support to sustain terrorism of this kind.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, those responsible cannot be mavericks acting
in isolation but part of a broader conspiracy to thwart local
development and peace," the ANC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, it asked residents in the Richmond area "not to allow
themselves to be provoked into actions that may lead to a spiral
of violence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
