<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NAA to Discuss New Trans-Atlantic Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Legislators from the 16 NATO
member states and 15 central and eastern European countries
gathered here today to discuss the future of the military alliance
and new trans-Atlantic relations.
</P>
<P>
Topics at the annual North Atlantic Assembly (NAA) session
included NATO in the next century, the costs of NATO enlargement,
the reform of the NATO military structure, trans-Atlantic trade in
relation to the defense industry, stability in the Balkans, the
status quo of the Russian armed forces and NATO partnership with
Romania.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also drew observers from Egypt, Japan, Sweden,
Canada, Austria and Switzerland, NAA Secretary General Simon Lunn
told the press today.
</P>
<P>
Consensus building is one of the primary purposes of the NAA
meeting that serves as a vehicle for alliance and central and
eastern European countries to convey national preoccupations and
concerns and inform one another of the different national and
regional perspectives that exist on many key issues.
</P>
<P>
NAA views are normally reflected in recommendations or
resolutions that are then either addressed to the North Atlantic
Council urging certain actions or addressed to NATO member
governments.
</P>
<P>
A plenary session is slated for next Monday when the NATO
secretary general, the Romanian prime minister, the presidents of
both the lower and upper houses of the Romanian parliament will
join the more than 300 parliamentarians on a debate on
"trans-Atlantic relations in a wider alliance."
</P>
<P>
Participating as associate countries in the four-day annual
session were Albania, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Macedonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Poland, Romania,
Russia, Slovakia, Slovenia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, then Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Poland and then the
Soviet Union were first granted associate country status in 1990
to attend the NAA meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that an NAA annual session was held in a
non-NATO country and Bucharest was chosen in recognition of the
progress Romania has made this year, according to the NAA
secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Romania is applying for accession to the North Atlantic
alliance.
</P>
<P>
While replying to a question from the host news service
Rompres, the NAA chief said the fact that a report describing
Romania as an "eligible candidate" for NATO expansion would be
submitted to the NAA committee for defense and security could
bolster the country's chance.
</P>
<P>
But Lunn was cautious as regards when Romania could be invited
to join NATO. It may depend on a smooth accession of Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic that were invited to join NATO at
its summit in Madrid last July.
</P>
<P>
Slovenia and the three Baltic states are also applying for NATO
membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
