<HEADLINE> European Shares Sharply down on European Rate Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
today were dealt a second blow by a sudden rise in European
interest rates following US Federal Reserve chief Alan Greenspan's
bearish comments Wednesday and all plunged sharply to end in the
negative grounds.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates rises in Germany and France dealt the London
market another body blow less than 24 hours after Alan Greenspan's
warning about inflation and unrealistic stock market expectations.
</P>
<P>
The rise in core European rates is being seen as a step toward
European economic and monetary union.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that rate sensitive bank and insurance stocks led
the retreat. The FTSE 100 index closed down 44.6 points at
5,217.5, but had been early 100 lower at worst. A rebound in the
Dow from an initial 90-point drop gave London a fillip.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index in Frankfurt closed the session 104.23 points
lower at 4,243.01. Shares were hit by the Bundesbank's decision to
raise its repo rate and Wall Street's sharp overnight decline.
</P>
<P>
The bank's decision to raise the rate to 3.3 percent from 3.0
percent pushed the DAX index down an extra 20 points on top of the
drop inspired by the slump in the Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, the CAC-40 index closed down 63.43 points
or more than two percent at 2,960.65 as French stocks came under
pressure following the Bank of France's interest rate rise today.
