<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Hotel Industry Faces Big Blow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- As many as 450 Turkish hotels
face huge losses ahead as their major tour operator is on verge of
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The insolvency challenging the Tursem, the third largest travel
agency in Turkey, will result in a drastic fall in the number of
tourists to the Aegean and Mediterranean resorts, the Turkish
Hotel Association (TUROB) warned today.
</P>
<P>
"The situation involving this company (Tursem) will lead to
the closure of some of the hotels affected," the TUROB said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 Turkish tourists and 8,000 foreign tourists
currently in those resorts will be flown home by other travel
agencies at the end of their vacations, it said.
</P>
<P>
Tursem's crisis was resulted from fluctuations in the value of
European currencies against the U.S. dollar, recent cash flow
problems as well as the cancellation of several large tours last
year.
</P>
<P>
The travel agency, which carried a total of 450,000 tourists to
Turkey and earned 84.6 million U.S. dollars in 1996, has asked for
help from the Turkish government and some international financial
groups.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Istanbul Monday, Tursem
Chairman Haluk Semiz urged Tursem's bank creditors to help it out
of the current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
At present, TUROB executives are reportedly holding talks with
the Turkish Tourism Ministry in Ankara to find a way to bail out
Tursem.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry is one of the major pillars for Turkish
economy. Around 8.9 million foreign tourists visited Turkey in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
