<HEADLINE> Intense Fighting Breaks out Across Congo River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Intense artillery exchanges
broke out today across the Congo River that separates cities of
Kinshasa and Brazzaville, Radio Cameroun reported.
</P>
<P>
Confusion spread through the streets of Kinshasa, capital of
the Democratic Republic of Congo, when it came under renewed
artillery and rocket attacks, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Two soldiers were killed and three others wounded when one
shell exploded at the gate of President Laurent Kabila's office.
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa responded by intensifying cannon and rocket fires
across the river, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
The attack appeared to be coming from the Brazzaville city
center, according to the radio.
</P>
<P>
No casualty figures were given for the counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa had already sent several hundred troops to
Brazzaville, especially on a mission to prevent artillery attacks
from its neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Last week, artillery shells killed 31 people in Kinshasa.
Democratic Congo had appealed to the United Nations Security
Council to discuss the Congo crisis to curb the escalation of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Brazzaville said more than 4,000 people have been
killed since the fighting erupted in June between the forces
loyal to Congolese President Pascal Lissouba and his rival former
President Sassou Nguesso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
