<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-09 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Government' Position on Trade Link Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Any commercial transactions
between Greek and Turkish Cypriots on the island should be
conducted within the framework of the existing constitutional and
legal order, a senior Cypriot government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his return from the U.S. where he attended a
meeting with U.S. business leaders, Finance Minister
Christodoulos Christodoulou said that under such conditions, the
Cypriot government does not object to the trade links between the
two communities before the solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in New York, which was also attended by Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and Central Bank Governor Afxentis
Afxentiou, was held at the initiative of U.S. presidential
emissary for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke has suggested that the two rival Cypriot communities
establish trade links as a step toward reconciliation between
them.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statement by Holbrooke about joint ventures
between the two communities on the island, Christodoulou said he
considers Holbrooke's plans to attract U.S. investment in Cyprus
as "natural," because Holbrooke is the vice chairman of the Credit
Swiss, one of the three largest banks in the world.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Cypriot government has clarified to
U.S. officials that if joint commercial transactions between
Greek and Turkish Cypriots are undertaken, they must be held
within the framework of the existing constitutional and legal
order with full recognition of the existing reality, the
independence and sovereignty of the Cyprus Republic.
</P>
<P>
If this is so, he added, "then the Cyprus government will not
object such transactions before a settlement."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north
and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the 37 percent of the island following a
short-lived pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has maintained a boycott of the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" since its
unilateral declaration of independence in 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
