<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Finance Reform Legislation Stalled in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Thursday
failed again to move forward legislation overhauling the campaign
finance system after an effort by moderate Republicans to forge a
compromise collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The Senate fell short of ending a Republican-led filibuster --
a deliberate measure of obstructing legislation by endless debate
-- against a bipartisan campaign finance bill, which is backed by
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
In a second vote, the Senate failed to end a Democratic-led
filibuster against a Republican amendment that would make it
tougher for unions to spend members' dues on political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
While Republicans oppose a package that doesn't protect union
members from having their dues used without their permission for
political purposes, and Democrats don't want unions singled out
without similar protection for members of other organizations and
to shareholders in corporations.
</P>
<P>
The vote to end debate on the campaign bill cosponsored by
Republican Senator John McCain of Arizona and Democratic Senator
Russell Feingold of Wisconsin was 52-47, eight short of the 60
votes required. It was the third defeat this week.
</P>
<P>
On Lott's amendment to require unions to get each member's
permission before using dues for political purposes, the vote was
51-48, nine short of the 60 needed. It was the second defeat this
week.
</P>
<P>
The McCain-Feingold bill would ban unlimited, unregulated
"soft-money" contributions to political parties and regulate
independent advertising campaigns by outside groups that promote a
specific candidate. It also would provide incentives for
politicians not to spend too much of their own money, impose new
disclosure requirements on campaign donations, and put into law a
Supreme Court decision letting non-union workers get reimbursed
for fees the union spends on political purposes.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator Mitch McConnell, who headed the effort to
fight the bill, said the McCain-Feingold bill is an
unconstitutional restriction on donations the Supreme court
contends are a protected form of free speech.
</P>
<P>
Democrats contend Lott's amendment regarding union dues is a
"poison pill" designed to undercut Democratic support for
McCain-Feingold.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
