<HEADLINE> Cameroun Marks Intl Day Against Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun has joined the concert
of nations to mark to preserve her adhesion to the global fight
against national catastrophes, a senior official has said here.
</P>
<P>
Andze Tsoungui, Vice Premier in charge of Territorial
Administration made the remarks Wednesday on the occasion of the
International Decade for the Prevention of Natural Catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
The International Decade for the Prevention of Natural
Catastrophes was launched in 1990 and will run into the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme is "Over-Abundance and Penury of Water:
Principal Cause of Natural Catastrophes."
</P>
<P>
The Vice Premier said Cameroun is a living victim of natural
catastrophes like the lake Nyos and lake Mamoun in 1986, that
killed more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
He called for intense sensitization and education of the
public on the impact of the catastrophes. 
</P>
