<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A Lebanese steel company suggested that the level of
duty on foreign imports return to 21 percent in a bid to curb
illegal dumping of sub-standard material.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese English-language newspaper Daily Star reported today
that Consolidated Steel, a leading steel company in Lebanon,
complained in a statement that foreign producers are taking
advantage of Lebanon's unregulated construction industry to dump
their sub-standard material.
</P>
<P>
The import of sub-standard foreign steel harms Lebanon's own
steel industry, causing the closure of steel production lines and
the redundancy of many workers, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Almost all these imports are produced in the former Soviet
Union and are of very low quality. They have a high carbon
content and are untraceable, the company said.
</P>
<P>
It appealed the government to take a temporary selective
measure to protect Lebanon from the illegal dumping and
introduce regulations on construction standards.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Libya today opened a joint gas and auto
service station in Sidi Barani on the Egyptian-Libyan borders.
</P>
<P>
It is the 5th of the 50 stations to be built by a joint
Egyptian-Libyan investment company in all parts of Egypt and on
the trunk roads between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The station was inaugurated by Egyptian Petroleum Minister
Hamdi Al-Banbi and Libyan Secretary of Energy Abdallah Al-Badri.
</P>
<P>
Banbi said that a 622-kilometer long oil pipeline will be also
constructed to pump 950,000 barrels of Libyan crude oil a day to
Egyptian oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The growth rate of Israel's industrial output
slacked up to only 2.4 percent in the January-July period, Israeli
Manufacturers Association said today.
</P>
<P>
The figure indicates there will be a 3 percent growth for the
whole year, the lowest in seven years, said Shuki Abramowitz, head
of the association's economics division.
</P>
<P>
According to a study the association conducted, the machinery
and equipment sector reported a slowdown of 6.3 percent in the
first six months of the year, whereas the textiles industry
experienced a 3.4 percent slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the rubber sand plastics sector had a 1.4 percent
slowdown and the non-metallic minerals industry slowed by 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
In contrast with these figures, the electronics components
sector reported a growth of 10.8 percent, while the
telecommunications equipment grew by 10.5 percent and the metals
industry grew by 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The number of visa credit card holders reached 1.9
million in the Middle East region by the end of last June,
representing a 46 percent growth over that a year earlier, Beirut
Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Visa expenditure in the Middle East amounted to 5.8 billion
U.S. dollars, registering an increase of 103 percent during the
year ending last June, the paper quoted Tony Brogna, area manager
for the Middle East Business Development for Visa, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Kuwait had the
lion's share in the volume of visa credit card use in the Middle
East. Iranian banks are also increasingly dealing with the cards
with two Iranian banks operating visa policies, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
