<HEADLINE> German Lower House Approves State Pension Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Bundestag, the lower house of
the German parliament, today approved a bill to reduce state
retirement pensions from the present 70 percent of average net
wages to 64 percent during the period from the year 2015 to 2030.
</P>
<P>
However, the main opposition Social Democratic Party vowed to
use its majority in the Bundesrat, the upper house of the German
parliament, to block the scheme.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government intends to keep the monthly
pension fund payments at its current level of 20.3 percent of
wages or salaries.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here said that the expenditure would rise to 20.8
percent next year unless the government further raises subsidy.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's government also considers raising value added tax to
16 percent from the current level of 15 percent to boost revenue
and offset the increase in pension contributions. 
</P>
