<HEADLINE> Russia, Kirghizstan to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Kirghiz Prime Minister Apas
Jumagulov and his Russian counterpart Viktor Chernomyrdin today
signed several agreements on strengthening cooperation over a wide
range of issues.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers signed the agreements on the sideline
of the summit of the 12-member Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS), held in Bishkek, capital of Kirghizstan. Chernomyrdin is
there for the summit and on an official visit.
</P>
<P>
Under one agreement, Russia and Kirghizstan will set up an
inter-governmental committee on economic, scientific and cultural
cooperation, while another agreement called for strengthening
cooperation in science, anti-drug war, military and defense.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said after the talks with Jumagulov that the
setting-up of the inter-governmental committee is the best way to
cooperate between Russia and Kirghizstan.
</P>
<P>
Jumagulov highlighted the importance of the inter-governmental
committee, saying the committee will supervise and coordinate the
implementation of bilateral agreements.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin went on to say that though Russia and Kirghizstan
have no plan to form a union in the near future, the two countries
are both committed to integration at higher levels.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the CIS is a good form of promoting
integration among member countries.
</P>
<P>
The CIS, which includes 12 of the 15 former Soviet republics,
was established as the Soviet Union dissolved at the end of
1991. It is intended to preserve and develop ties between the
republics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
