<HEADLINE> Dunhuang Documents Returned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Applause erupted when Aoyama
Keiji from Japan presented eight ancient Dunhuang documents to
Duan Wenjie, president of the Dunhuang Research Institute,
</P>
<P>
"This marks the first time a foreigner has returned intact
Dunhuang documents to China," said Duan, adding that an untold
number of Dunhuang relics remain scattered abroad.
</P>
<P>
Experts conducted a precise appraisal and concluded that the
aforementioned valuable documents, each of which dates back at
least 1,000 years, came from a cave in the Mogao Grottos in
northwest China's Gansu province.
</P>
<P>
Early this century, a Taoist priest by the name of Wang Yuanlu
quite unexpectedly discovered that a cave in Mogao was filled with
tens of thousands of ancient documents, Buddhist sutras and arts
and crafts.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the relics were seized by so-called 'western
explorers' within a short period of five years," said Duan.
</P>
<P>
A survey revealed that Dunhuang documents and relics are
currently in collections in 14-odd foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 10 years, Chinese experts have called on the
countries in question to return Dunhuang relics to China, or to
otherwise return some for exhibitions. The experts note that their
appeals fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the importance of Dunhuang relics is enhanced when
they are returned to the place of their origin," said Aoyama
Keiji. The Japanese benefactor said that he inherited the
treasures from his father Aoyama Sanu, who had purchased them 10
years earlier in a Tokyo bookstore selling ancient documents.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Research Institute plans to hold a series of
activities in 1999 to mark the 100th anniversary of the discovery
of the cave which held priceless Buddhist sutras. Collectors known
to have Dunhuang documents will be invited to attend the
exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
