<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Probe Toxic Toy Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Health Department of Canada
will probe claims by Greenpeace that vinyl toys and other products
for children contain hazardous levels of lead and cadmium.
</P>
<P>
The products will be tested to determine if they contain toxic
levels of lead and cadmium, and if so, whether those metals are
released in a form that can be absorbed by human bodies, local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Test results are expected within two weeks, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Greenpeace study found high levels of lead and cadmium in a
variety of Canadian products made from PVC plastic, also known as
vinyl. The products include toys, raincoats, backpacks and key
rings.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever there is lead in products we are always concerned," a
spokesman for the health department was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Last year, parents of Canadian children under seven were warned
to get rid of mini-blinds made from PVC.
</P>
<P>
Lead has been linked to reduced intelligence, and cadmium can
cause kidney damage, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
