<HEADLINE> Party Congress Expected to Promote Trade Across Taiwan Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- China's intent to accelerate
reforms and open wider to the outside world in the wake of the
15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China will
provide new opportunities for economic and trade cooperation
between both sides of the Taiwan Straits, according to a senior
Chinese official.
</P>
<P>
The report Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), presented to the
15th Party Congress reiterated China's basic policy on Taiwan and
exhibited the mainland's sincere desire to promote trade
cooperation, according to Wang Hui, deputy director of the Taiwan,
Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Department under the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Bilateral economic cooperation fully accords with the objective
law of development despite the restrictions the Taiwan authorities
have placed on investments in the mainland of China. A new surge
of investment is bound to accompany increasing opportunities, said
Wang.
</P>
<P>
The cross-Straits trade volume has witnessed rapid development
since China introduced economic reforms in 1978. The trade volume
has grown by an annual average rate of 27 percent and soared from
7.4 billion US dollars in 1992 to 18.9 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investments have grown by 15.4-fold to 14.2 billion US
do over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of Taiwan investment to total overseas investments on
the Chinese mainland has jumped from 1.1 percent to seven percent,
said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He added that Taiwan investors have expanded their scope of
investment from labor-intensive industries to the energy,
infrastructure and high technology sectors in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Wang urged the Taiwan Authorities to refrain from blocking
economic cooperation between the two sides due to the divergence
of political opinions and to remove restrictions preventing local
industrial and commercial sectors from investing on the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
