<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Illegal Currency Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Institutions and individuals
are prohibited from dealing in Chinese Renminbi yuan in
circulation, while Renminbi-denominated banknotes and coins
withdrawn from circulation can be traded on the market.
</P>
<P>
The notice issued by the People's Bank of China (PBOC) and the
State Administration for Industry and Commerce (SAIC) calls for
full implementation of the State Council General Office circular
on halting illegal currency transactions.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary commemorative coins cannot be traded at prices higher
than face-value within the first year of issuance, while
commemorative gold and silver coins can be traded at market
prices, according to the notice.
</P>
<P>
A limited volume of ornamental banknotes and coins can be
traded on the market for cultural exchange purposes.
</P>
<P>
All currency dealers are required to obtain approval from
provincial branches of the PBOC and register with local SAIC
offices. The China Gold Coin Company is the only authorized dealer
of China's commemorative gold and silver coins
</P>
<P>
The notice calls for strict scrutiny of the nation's coin
markets, and emphasizes that financial institutions and their
staffers are strictly prohibited from involvement in illegal
currency transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
