<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Exiled Assembly Members Urged to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian National Assembly
(parliament) President Chea Sim and First Deputy President Loy Sim
Chheag today called on exiled assembly members abroad to return
home for parliament sessions scheduled for later this month.
</P>
<P>
An appeal, which was jointly signed by Chea Sim and Loy Sim
Chheag, warned that those who fail to return home before the
deadline of October 28 will lose their membership of parliament
automatically.
</P>
<P>
The appeal said it was understandable that some assembly
members temporarily left their home country before and after the
"July Incident" over worries about an imminent war in Cambodia or
possible violence threatening their personal safety.
</P>
<P>
"But now the tension in both the capital city of Phnom Penh and
other areas in the country has eased and life has returned to
normal," the appeal said. It urged the assembly members still
abroad to return home and fulfill their duties before October 28.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure the general elections to be held as
scheduled in May next year, the Cambodian National Assembly will
discuss and pass the election law and party law by the end of
October, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
There are still 15 Cambodian assembly members from Funcinpec
Party and Khmer Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party, living in exile
abroad, including National Assembly Second Deputy President Son
Sou Ber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
