<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, October 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS -- A Palestinian official has denied circulating reports
about a U.S.-Israeli-Jordanian plot against the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview carried by Friday's Tunisian
newspaper Al Shorouq, Mohammad Abas (Abu Mazen), Secretary General
of Palestine Liberation Organization Executive Committee and
Arafat's Deputy, said he was not aware of reports claiming that
PNA President Yasser Arafat, at a closed meeting of the
Palestinian Council, had revealed a "U.S.-Israeli-Jordanian plot"
aimed at bypassing the PNA.
</P>
<P>
He said such reports are not credible unless they directly
emanated from Arafat's office. No one else is empowered to make
such statements, he added. (PNA-Israel-Plot)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- The 1997 Nobel Peace Prize Friday was awarded to
the International Campaign to Ban Landmines (ICBL) and its
coordinator Jody Williams.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian Nobel Committee said it made the decision as a
recognition of the co-winners' "work in the banning and clearing
of anti-personnel mines." (Nobel-Peace Prize)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- A senior South Korean government official Friday denied
a Los Angeles Times report that President Kim Young-sam may have
donated 50,000 U.S. dollars to then-presidential candidate Bill
Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The report, which alleged the purpose of the donation as to
secure U.S. endorsement for Kim's candidacy in the South Korean
presidential race, is "totally groundless," said a top
presidential aide, under the customary condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"We have instructed the South Korean embassy in the United
States to look into the circumstances of that report," the aide
said, adding that the government plans to rebuke the Los Angeles
Times after receiving the embassy's report. (SKorea-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government said Friday that it is
optimistic about getting financial assistance from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in overcoming the rupiah's
steady weakening.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here, Finance Minister Mar'ie
Muhammad expressed the hope that Indonesia and IMF could reach a
consensus on long-term loans because the country's economic
fundamental is still strong. (Indonesia-IMF-Assistance)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In a move to amend the damaged relations with
Canada, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy has apologized to
Canada for the use of forged Canadian passports by two Israeli
agents in an attack on a Hamas leader.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Friday that Levy sent a message to his
Canadian counterpart Lloyd Axworthy to offer the apology and
expressed the hope that this could ease the tension between the
two countries. (Israel-Canada-Apology) 
</P>
