<HEADLINE> First Batch of Iranian Visitors Arrives in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The first group of Iranians
arrived in Iraq today across the Al Waleed border post to visit
Shiite Muslim holy shrines, an Iraqi official said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Iraqi News Agency, Sirowan Abdul Qader,
Chairman of the Iraqi Tourist Authority, said that other Iranian
groups would be arriving in Iraq successively in the coming few
days.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Iraqi Al Hoda company for religious tourism
would provide the necessary and best facilities to the Iranian
visitors to perform their prayers at the holy sites in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He failed to mention where the Iranian visitors come
from. Iraq said earlier that it had agreed to receive seven
groups of overseas Iranians from the Gulf region and the United
States despite Iran's doubt over Baghdad's intention of doing so.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced on September 4 that it would open its borders
to Iranians, for the first time since the war between the two
countries broke out in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the only Shiite-dominated country in the region but
the most important Shiite shrines are in Iraq. 
</P>
