<HEADLINE> Editorial to Hail Forthcoming World Petroleum Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- People's Daily, China's leading
national newspaper, will carry an editorial tomorrow, hailing the
forthcoming 15th World Petroleum Congress and extending a warm
welcome to friends from throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the congress, the first of its kind to be held in
a developing country, will be held in China indicates the
increasing strength and rising international status of the
nation's petroleum industry, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The congress will also provide an excellent opportunity for
China to learn more about advanced technology and management in
other countries, it added.
</P>
<P>
The concerted efforts of all participants will ensure that the
congress will foster a new era for the world's petroleum industry,
and the industry will in turn make greater contributions to the
prosperity of the global economy and the progress of human
society, the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has consistently placed great emphasis
on developing oil and gas resources since the founding of New
China in 1949 when the nation's annual crude oil production stood
at a mere 120,000 tons, it noted.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, however, China's 24 major oil and gas production
centers ranked fifth in the world with annual production of 157
million tons, and natural gas output of 20.1 billion cu.m., the
editorial pointed out.
</P>
<P>
China currently has more than 20 large petro-chemical
enterprises with a combined annual refining capacity of 230
million tons of crude oil, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
