<HEADLINE> Sino-Kazakh Oil Field Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen Chinese petroleum
specialists left Urumqi, capital of northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, today for Alma-Ata to participate in the
joint management of an oilfield in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The team will work at the Aktyubinsk Oilfield in accordance
with a contract between the China Oil and Gas Corp. and the
Kazakhstan Ministry of Natural Resources. The Chinese company
bought 60 percent of the shares of the oilfield.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield has an estimated oil reserve of 130 million tons
and annual crude oil output of about 2.6 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The two nations have also agreed to explore for other oil
deposits in Kazakhstan, and will lay a 3000-km oil pipeline to
Xinjiang and a second pipeline to northern Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
