<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Anticipates Rising Steel Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Projections call for China's
annual steel output of between 105-115 million tons by the end of
the century to basically meet the needs for domestic economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The steel industry will expand efforts to gain the lion's share
of the domestic market and will increase its competitiveness on
the international market, according to Niu Dongchun, an official of
the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The sector, which anticipates an influx of 300 billion yuan in
investments during the 1996-2000 period, will place priority on
upgrading existing enterprises, and producing steel and stainless
steel products for the automobile, petroleum, power generation
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The government will encourage various qualified enterprises to
either establish ventures abroad in order to develop and produce
resources in short supply, including iron ore and pellets, or sign
long-term contracts with foreign countries for raw materials.
</P>
<P>
China's 1996 steel output of 101.23 million tons ranked the
country as the world's largest steel producer. Nonetheless, the
steel industry continues to lag far behind other countries in
terms of production technique and equipment.
</P>
<P>
China will need 110-120 million tons of steel by the end of the
century based on an expected average annual eight percent growth
in GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
