<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Campaign to Address Health Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The National Mental Health
Week, a fresh campaign to address the wide-spreading problem of
mental disorder in Sri Lanka, started today.
</P>
<P>
Under a directive issued by President Chandrika Kumaratunga,
the Ministry of Health and Indigenous Medicine launched the
campaign today to raise public awareness of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 70,000 mental patients
in the country. Experts said the main cause to commit suicide in
Sri Lanka was mental disorder.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the ministry said the government would establish
mental health wards in every district hospital shortly to help
patients seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the first wards will be set up in Kataragama
and Badulla in Uva Province.
</P>
<P>
A series of activities, including art performances, cartoon
shows and exhibitions, will be held during the week.  
