<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Three More Satellites This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- China is to launch three more
satellites within this year, including one telecommunications
satellite and two iridium satellites, Wang Liheng, vice-president
of China Aerospace Corporation, said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing for the Second China International Aerospace
and Aviation Exhibition (China Airshow '98), due in November next
year, he said that China planned to launch a telecom satellite
with home-made Long March 3B rocket in about ten days.
</P>
<P>
The improved model of the Long March 2C has already been used
for the trial launching of an iridium satellite this year.
</P>
<P>
China this year has successfully sent the home-made
Dongfanghong-3 telecom satellite and FY-2 meteorological satellite
into the orbit. Also, the country sent off last August
Mabuhaysat, a telecom satellite made by the US-based Space System
for the Philippine Mabuhay Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
He said that all the results were accomplished one year after
the first China Airshow '96.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the technical level of China-made satellites
have reached the international standards in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Also, China has developed its own Long March rocket family, of
which the propelling capacity of Long March 3B to send a
satellite into the geo-synchronous orbit has hit 5,000 kg. "That
can meet the demands of about 90 percent of the international
commercial launching," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
China has also made progress in other applications, including
space seed-breeding, satellite disaster reduction and innovation
of traditional industries with space technologies. The seeds
cultivated in the space can increase 10 percent of per-unit grain
yield, contributing to China's plan to increase 50 billion kg of
grain in its Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
