<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, U.S. to Forge Accord on Status of Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and the United
States are expected to eventually forge a new Status of Forces
Agreement (SOFA) between them before the end of this year, a
senior Philippine diplomat said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Undersecretary Rodolfo Severino said the
conclusion of a new SOFA with the U.S. could even be materialized
this month if U.S. representatives will be able to come here to
finalize the draft agreement they have been working on since late
last year.
</P>
<P>
Severino, who just came back home from the U.S. where he had
another round of talks on the SOFA, said that both sides desire to
conclude an agreement but that they are yet unable to agree on the
remaining contentious points.
</P>
<P>
He declined to divulge the remaining points of disagreement,
but stressed they don't involve the issues of "immunity" and
"permanent presence of U.S. forces in the country or even U.S.
access to Philippine military bases."
</P>
<P>
The new SOFA accord, Severino explained, is based on the
existing Philippines-U.S. Mutual Defense Treaty (MDT).
</P>
<P>
The regular annual joint military exercises have been
temporarily suspended pending the conclusion of the new SOFA
accord that will provide the exercises a legal basis.
</P>
<P>
Besides the United States, the Philippines has been negotiating
separately with Britain and some other countries on similar
accords on the status of foreign soldiers participating in joint
war games on the Philippine territory.
</P>
<P>
The old SOFA between the United States and the Philippines
ended with the termination of the Philippines-U.S. Bases Agreement
in 1991, under which American troops pulled out of Subic Naval
Base, the last U.S. base in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new SOFA accord, once finalized, will have yet to be
ratified by the Philippine Senate before it could be operational.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Official Denies US-Israeli-Jordanian Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian official has
denied circulating reports about a U.S.-Israeli-Jordanian plot
against the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview carried by today's Tunisian newspaper
Al Shorouq, Mohammad Abas (Abu Mazen), Secretary General of
Palestine Liberation Organization Executive Committee and Arafat's
Deputy, said he was not aware of reports claiming that PNA
President Yasser Arafat, at a closed meeting of the Palestinian
Council, had revealed a "U.S.-Israeli-Jordanian plot" aimed at
bypassing the PNA.
</P>
<P>
He said such reports are not credible unless they directly
emanated from Arafat's office. No one else is empowered to make
such statements, he added.
</P>
<P>
On circulating reports that Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy was considering resignation on the grounds that he has been
ignored by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on many
occasions, Abu Mazen said that Netanyahu's differences with Levy
are overt and commonplace. But he doubted whether this could
actually lead to Levy's resignation.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Levy complained about not being informed in
advance of the attempted murder attack on Hamas leader Khaled
Mashaal in Jordan last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
