<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997 Nobel Peace Prize Goes to ICBL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 Nobel Peace Prize
today was awarded to the International Campaign to Ban Landmines
(ICBL) and its coordinator Jody Williams.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian Nobel Committee said it made the decision as a
recognition of the co-winners' "work in the banning and clearing
of anti-personnel mines."
</P>
<P>
The ICBL and Jody Williams have made the ban on anti-personnel
mines from a vision to a feasible reality in a few years, the
committee said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the ICBL's efforts, an international treaty against
landmines will be signed in Ottawa this December.
</P>
<P>
The ICBL is a network with over 1,000 member organizations,
"through which it has been possible to express and mediate a broad
wave of popular commitment in an unprecedented way."
</P>
<P>
Currently, over 100 million anti-personnel mines are scattered
over large areas of land on several continents.
</P>
<P>
Such mines pose a major threat to the safety of civilians as
well as the social and economic development of the countries
affected.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian Nobel Committee calls for wider support for the
Ottawa process, viewing it as a model for similar processes in the
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
