<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes Key Construction Market for South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean overseas builders
are experiencing a second "golden time" from the early 1980s, with
China, Singapore and Indonesia having become its key overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Contractors Association of
Korea, South Korean companies won contracts amounting to 1.53
billion U.S. dollars from China during the January-September
period, up 157.7 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This was the largest number of contracts that South Korean
firms have ever earned from China in history.
</P>
<P>
South Korean companies received orders valued at 9.7 billion
dollars from abroad in the first nine months this year, a 45
percent increase over the same period last year, the Ministry of
Construction and Transportation said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, domestic companies placed orders worth 1.44 billion
dollars and 1.03 billion dollars with Singapore and Indonesia in
the first nine months, up 100 percent and 124 percent from the
same period of last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, cooperation with India, the United States
and Malaysia have scaled down dramatically despite fertile
cooperation in the past.
</P>
<P>
India, the largest market for South Korea last year, have
fallen to the fourth place with 940 million dollars this year,
only 64.3 percent of that in last year.
</P>
<P>
Orders from the United States and Malaysia were also reported
declining this year, standing at only 296 million dollars and 126
million dollars, which increased 8.5 percent and 27 percent
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
