<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fischer's Visit to Malaysia Overshadowed By Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Prime Minister Tim
Fischer's trade mission to Kuala Lumpur next week is overshadowed
by Malaysia's decision to overlook an Australia's bid for a 1.45
billion U.S. dollars defense contract.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who is also trade minister, is due to sign a new
bilateral trade pact with Malaysia next week, replacing a 1958
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The visit will now follow the loss by Australia's Transfield
Defense Systems of a major bid to supply the Malaysian navy with
up to 27 new patrol ships.
</P>
<P>
Fischer expressed his disappointment over ABC Radio today that
Malaysia had chosen a German company over Transfield.
</P>
<P>
He blamed former prime minister Paul Keating's description of
Malaysia's leader Mahathir Mohamad as "recalcitrant" four years
ago, saying it may have contributed to the loss.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of foreign affairs and trade today
attempted to play down speculation that the old diplomatic row had
contributed to the loss, saying it was too early to tell what had
led to Malaysia's decision.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite clear the government is very disappointed at the
outcome but at the same time, it seems the decision has been taken
on commercial grounds. There is nothing to indicate to us
otherwise," officials were quoted by Australian Associated Press
as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they were not sure if they could secure a
meeting between Fischer and Mahathir because the Malaysian leader
was preparing to announce his budget next Friday.
</P>
<P>
But they stressed that Australia had worked hard to improve
diplomatic ties with Mahathir and they were trying to make
arrangement for Prime Minister John Howard's first visit to the
country.
</P>
<P>
"It's simply a question of timing and more likely (to take
place) next year," they added.
</P>
<P>
A defense ministry spokesman in Kuala Lumpur was reported to
refused to comment on the patrol ships contract today, although a
shipping industry source said it had been awarded to an
unidentified company four days earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
