<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Burns 2.5 Million Fraud Letters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian authorities have burnt
2.5 million letters written by Advanced Fee Fraud plotters in
Lagos, the Punch newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that they burnt Tuesday the letters filling
150 mail bags, intercepted at the Lagos international airport
between January 1996 and March 1997, by the Telecommunications
and Post Offenses Task Force.
</P>
<P>
Chiroma Wandeo, an official of the task force, said the
letters were affixed with illegal franking stamps and forged
postage stamps valued at the 70 million Naira (about 850,000 U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Seventeen staff of the Nigerian Postal Services and the
National Cargo Handling Company have been arrested and are being
investigated for involvement in the offenses, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Advanced Fee Fraud is also widely known as 419 crime for the
section 419 of the Nigerian Criminal Code against it. It has
become so rampant in the last few years that the government has
to introduce a special law against it in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The cheaters often send out thousands of letters to overseas
promising lucrative business opportunities in Nigeria and
persuade the victims to pay an advanced fee to get the money. In
one case, a victim was cheated five million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
