<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Consolidates After Strong Job Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
weaker today against the U.S. dollar, but traders said sentiment
remains positive and the currency is primed for moving higher.
</P>
<P>
The September labor force report released yesterday has
effectively capsized previous high expectations in the market that
the Reserve Bank of Australia would move to ease monetary policy
in the short term.
</P>
<P>
Stronger than expected housing finance data posted today by the
 Australian Bureau of Statistics offered no cheer to the market.
Seasonally adjusted housing finance rose by 7.8 percent in August,
compared to average market expectations of a 4.7-percent advance.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 73.63 U.S. cents, down from 73.87
previously.
</P>
<P>
"It has consolidated fairly well around these sorts of levels,"
said a St. George Bank trader. "If anything we are looking for a
move up."
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, the currency jumped by nearly 1.5 U.S. cents on the
back of stronger than expected jobs data.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar has recovered on the back of the more
favorable growth outlook and the change in interest rate
sentiment," Citibank economists said in a commentary.
</P>
<P>
"These trends, plus the prospect of further gains in commodity
prices, could drive the Australian dollar higher over the medium
term."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 88.71 Japanese yen, up from 88.49
yesterday, and at 1.2841 Deutsche marks, from 1.2921.  
</P>
</TEXT>
