<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Denies U.S. Media Report on Kim's Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior South Korean government
official today denied a Los Angeles Times report that President
Kim Young-sam may have donated 50,000 U.S. dollars to
then-presidential candidate Bill Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The report, which alleged the purpose of the donation as to
secure U.S. endorsement for Kim's candidacy in the South Korean
presidential race, is "totally groundless," said a top
presidential aide, under the customary condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"We have instructed the South Korean embassy in the United
States to look into the circumstances of that report," the aide
said, adding that the government plans to rebuke the Los Angeles
Times after receiving the embassy's report.
</P>
<P>
The government will file a formal protest against the newspaper
and demand correction of the inaccurate report, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. paper reported on Thursday that two Democratic
fund-raisers are prepared to testify that President Clinton's 1992
campaign had given an endorsement to a candidate for a political
office in Asia in exchange for a 50,000 dollar contribution.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted "investigators" as saying that the "candidate
for political office in Asia" may have been South Korean President
Kim Young-sam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
