<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Stabilize This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian Wool prices
stabilized after sharp drops last week, the Australian Council of
Wool Exporters said in its weekly market review today.
</P>
<P>
The eastern indicator rose six cents to close at 705 Australian
cents (518 U.S. cents) a clean kilogram while the western
indicator, catching up with last week's movements, dropped 18
Australian cents to finish at 642 Australian cents (472 U.S.
cents).
</P>
<P>
A total of 92,252 bales were offered at Sydney, Adelaide and
Fremantle with a pass-in rate of 12.2 per cent.
</P>
<P>
"While the three centers selling this week were quite different
in terms of their composition of offerings and market environment,
the overall outcome for the week was as good, if not better, than
most exporters would have forecast at the start of the week," the
council said.
</P>
<P>
Competition remained widespread across most sectors of the
trade.
</P>
<P>
"It does appear, however, that the market is mainly supply
driven at present as quantities on offer are not exceptionally
large for what is traditionally the peak offering period for the
season," the council said.
</P>
<P>
In its wool weekly report, Wesfarmers Dalgety said the
stabilization provided an encouraging outlook for the next sales.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed to a smaller offering next week which
included stylish and fine clips in strong demand.
</P>
<P>
"The only possible dampening factor is the strength of the
Australian dollar which jumped a cent to 73.75 U.S. cents
yesterday," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Generally, however, the outlook for next week's market is for
prices to remain firm if not increase," it added.
</P>
<P>
About 91,300 bales are rostered for sale next week at Goulburn,
Melbourne and Fremantle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
