<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Wanes as Banks Tumble Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- A second day of solid falls
among bank stocks and the bluechips dragged the Australian share
market to a sub-2700 point close.
</P>
<P>
Another negative finish on Wall Street overnight also ensured
weak sentiment prevailed, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index shed 27.7 points to close at
2694.5 after hitting an intraday low of 2683.0.
</P>
<P>
This follows yesterday's 46.2 point deterioration, a loss of
1.67 per cent, to 2722.2.
</P>
<P>
"The banks took another hit but we don't necessarily think
there is too much more pain around," BNP Equities broker John
Bowie-Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
"Other market leaders suffered again. People will be watching
closely how Wall Street fares tonight for some direction on
Monday."
</P>
<P>
Overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 33.64 points
to 8061.42 after recovering from an early 92-point drop.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the bank index tumbled 111.5 points or 2.06 per cent
to finish at 5299.4.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials fared less badly, dropping 47.4 points to
4428.1, while the resources sector slipped only 11.9 to 1330.9.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, NAB fell 46 cents, ANZ erased 42, CBA ended
39.7 weaker and Westpac dipped nine cents.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP ended 13 cents down, Rio Tinto shed 15.1,
WMC fell 17, Woodside Petroleum finished 16.5 worse.
</P>
<P>
National turnover topped 533 million shares and exceeded 1.1
billion Australian dollars (803 million US dollars) in value, with
falls easily outpacing rises 729 to 426.  
</P>
</TEXT>
