<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NAA Ponders on Wider Area of NATO Responsibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 10 (Xinhua) -- NATO legislators have to
remind themselves of the probability of stretching the military
alliance's responsibility to outside the transatlantic area.
</P>
<P>
The question of whether NATO should define a wider area of
responsibility was asked when the North Atlantic Assembly (NAA)
session started today.
</P>
<P>
Jan Petersen, a Norwegian delegate to the annual meeting, told
participants that NATO in the next century should clarify what
risks outside the NATO treaty area might engage the 16-nation
alliance.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot foresee future contingencies and whether the
alliance as a whole or only some members may choose to act," said
Petersen, hinting at such crisis-laden spots in non-NATO countries
as the Mideast and Africa.
</P>
<P>
NATO strategists are worried that as NATO shifts its strategic
focus from mainly defending its members from potential attacks to
crisis management, the alliance will have to look into problem
areas immediately outside NATO and far-flung places that are rich
in natural resources key to NATO members.
</P>
<P>
The delegates agreed that NATO provides the natural core around
which a future European security order has to be built.
</P>
<P>
Petersen said at today's meeting that the North Atlantic
alliance has always been more than a mere insurance policy against
a threat from the east.
</P>
<P>
It is forging a transatlantic community of democracies and by
projecting the community eastward to include more central and
eastern countries helps shape a stable and democratic security
environment.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian asked why NATO cannot perform collective security
tasks while maintaining a robust collective defense capability
thanks to its unique integrated military structure.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that NATO does not need a threat to justify its
existence or its enlargement, he urged the annual session to
consider spelling out NATO's mandate, its rationale and new
missions in a new strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
The previous such concept was drawn out in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Delegates shared the view that the Madrid summit, at which
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic were invited to join the
alliance, was a significant yet incomplete step toward a "new
NATO." Further expansion is needed to make the security
integration complete for all Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Russia must also be part of this integration," said the
Norwegian.
</P>
<P>
Legislators from the 16 NATO member states and 15 Central and
Eastern European countries are attending the Bucharest meeting,
which also drew observers from as far as Australia, Japan
alongside Egypt, Israel, Morocco, Tunisia, Georgia, Finland,
Sweden, Canada and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Participating as associate countries in the four-day session
are Albania, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Macedonia,
Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Russia,
Slovakia, Slovenia and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
