<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan FM Hails U.S. Ban Against LTTE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman kadirgamar said today that the U.S. decision to ban the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) from entering and raising
fund in the United States was "one of the weapons to use in
combating international terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"From now on, anybody who contributes to the LTTE in the U.S.
will be charged with criminal offenses," the minister told a news
conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The only way in combating international terrorism today is to
have a concerted international action, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that one of the wider consequences of the U.S. action
was "other governments would be requested by the Government of
U.S. to take due heed to this declaration and to take supportive
measures in their own countries."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madelene Albright on Wednesday
announced the LTTE, along with the other 29 organizations in the
world, was on the terrorist organization list that would be barred
from entering and raising fund in the United States.
</P>
<P>
She said members of the listed groups would be ineligible for
visas to enter the U.S. and that their funds would be frozen under
a new anti-terrorism law signed by American President Bill Clinton
in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar just concluded his visit to the United States on
Wednesday night. During his visit to the United States, the
foreign minister stressed Sri Lanka's request to the U.S. to
declare the LTTE as a terrorist organization while meeting with
Albright.
</P>
<P>
"The Tamil people in the north and east have suffered from the
war for 14 years. I believe there is a great hunger among the
Tamil people for peace," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Tamil compatriots in other countries to use
whatever financial resources they have to rebuild and reconstruct
the northern and eastern parts of the country that are affected by
war and not to use that money for bombs and bullets.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 14-year ethnic war in the north
and east of Sri Lanka for an independent state of their own. So
far the war has claimed 55,000 people of their lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
