<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Fluoridize Drinking Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will publish
draft regulations on the fluoridation of drinking water next
month, local daily The Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The regulations had been approved by the ministries of
environmental affairs, agriculture, and water affairs, Health
Minister Nkosazana Zuma was quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Zuma told the Sixth World Congress on Preventive
Dentistry being held in Cape Town that the introduction of
community water fluoridation was part of a drive to make
preventive dentistry a reality.
</P>
<P>
"Introducing fluoridation will go a long way towards improving
oral and dental health and is a great step forward for South
Africa," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the cost of adjusting the existing fluoride
concentration in the country's water supply was about one Rand
(one U.S. Dollar equals to 4.70 Rand) per person a year.
</P>
<P>
This made fluoridation an attractive public health measure
because it was 18 times cheaper than using fluoridized
toothpaste, and 61 times cheaper than filling a tooth, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to a medical survey, more than 90 of every 100 South
Africans experienced some tooth decay by the time they reached
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
However, local dental experts believed that a small
concentration of fluoride in water could reduce tooth decay by
about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Millions of South Africans could benefit from this primary
preventive measure, particularly those communities who had
neither the access nor the resources to benefit from the
commercially available fluoride alternatives, they said.
</P>
<P>
Usuf Chikte, Chairman of the congress's scientific committee,
said South Africa was one of the first country in sub-Saharan
Africa to introduce fluoridation.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 major international health organizations,
including the World Health Organization and the International
Dental Federation, supported water fluoridation, and more than
300 million people worldwide benefit from community water
fluoridation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
