<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Optimistic About IMF Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government said
today that it is optimistic about getting financial assistance
from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in overcoming the
rupiah's steady weakening.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here this afternoon, Finance
Minister Mar'ie Muhammad expressed the hope that Indonesia and IMF
could reach a consensus on long-term loans because the country's
economic fundamental is still strong.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie, who met with a team of IMF officials this morning, said
he briefed the officials on Indonesia's current economic situation
and the two sides discussed several issues related to IMF aid
Indonesia is seeking for.
</P>
<P>
At the same press conference, Minister for Industry and Trade
Tungky Ariwibowo and Bank Indonesia (central bank) Governor
Soedradjad Djiwndono believed that it is possible for Indonesia, a
big country in Southeast Asia, to get IMF aid as the country has
closer cooperation ties with international financial institutions,
including IMF and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie noted that the Indonesian rupiah has depreciated by
around 46 percent since January 1997. The rupiah has been
particularly hard hit in the regional monetary crisis which also
hit the Thai bath, Philippine peso, Malaysian ringgit and
Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, he pledged that the rupiah will continue to float
although the government will take all necessary market-friendly
measures to avoid an excessive depreciation of the currency.
</P>
<P>
To stabilize the rupiah, the Indonesian government has taken
several steps since mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The measures include revising the budget to keep it in balance,
boosting export and containing import in a GATT-consistent manner
and deferring some government- and state-owned enterprise
projects, as well as private-sector projects amounting to
approximately 35 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government also initiated structural measures, including
deregulation measures to enhance its efficiency and
competitiveness, to strengthen the financial sector and maintain
prudent monetary policies through appropriate liquidity and
interest rate policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
