<HEADLINE> Central Chinese Province Opens Agriculture to Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- China's Hunan province has
approved 572 overseas-funded agriculture projects in the past five
years, involving 390 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
That was more than half of the total amount the province used
during the 15-year period after China started its reforms and
opening-up in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Hunan held a trade fair last month, and got 14 agriculture
co-operation agreements, with nearly 300 million US dollars worth
of investment from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The province has natural conditions that favor agriculture,
with 3.31 million ha of farmland, 8.32 million ha of forests, and
1.35 million ha of ponds or lakes.
</P>
<P>
It listed 12 key agriculture-related projects for overseas
participation during the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), mainly
involving wheat, cotton, oil-bearing crops, tea, tobacco,
pig-raising, aquatics, and cottage industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
