<HEADLINE> India to Have Computer Institute by Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The National Software
Companies Association (NASSCOM) is making efforts to train more
computer software professionals and its computer training
institute will start functioning in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Called the Institute of Computer Software Professionals of
India (ICSPI), it would add 5,000 quality professionals to the
software professional pool annually by 2002, NASSCOM Executive
Director Dewang Mehta said here today.
</P>
<P>
With demand for qualified computer professionals expected to
increase 10-fold in the next five years, the institute will play a
crucial role in allowing India to retain its competitive edge in
the global software industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
There is currently a large floating population of
computer-literate workers, who require additional education and
training to become useful for employment in the software industry.
The institute would focus on tapping the potential of such people
and it is expected to produce 15,000 professionals annually by the
year 2005, Mehta added.  
</P>
