<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Invited to Attend Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL)
Secretary-General Esmat Abdul-Meguid has received an official
invitation to attend the Middle East and North African Economic
Conference (MENA) to be held in Qatari capital Doha in November.
</P>
<P>
The invitation from Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin
Jassim Bin Jabir al-Thani came during Abdul-Meguid's meeting here
Thursday night with Qatari Ambassador to Egypt and its chief
delegate to the Arab League Mane Al-Hajeri and Abdel Rahman
Attiya, an official at the Qatari Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Attiya said he discussed with the Arab
League chief the latest developments in the Middle East in
particular and the Arab region in general.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Attiya insisted that Qatar is not
deviating from the Arab stance vis-a-vis the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Despite the threat to boycott the conference by some Arab
countries, Qatar insists on hosting it on November 16. Saudi
Arabia and Syria flatly rejected the conference due to Israel's
participation, while Egypt had been saying that its participation
hinges on progress on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only two Arab countries that have
peace treaties with Israel, with which Qatar has limited trade
ties.
</P>
<P>
As a direct spinoff of the Mideast peace process, the annual
MENA conference had been held in Casablanca, Morocco; in Amman,
Jordan and in Cairo, Egypt since 1994. But peace prospects have been
largely deteriorated since then.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process came to a halt since
March when Israel began the construction of a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But a surprise summit early Wednesday between Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat might signal a new start in efforts to
save the peace process. It was their first meeting in eight
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
