<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urbanization Means Change for East China's Rural Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Lin Youzeng and millions of
other rural residents have been swept up and are no longer farmers
in the tide of urbanization in some coastal areas of China.
</P>
<P>
"I have come to realize that to be an urban resident means more
than just the change of the job," said Lin, 55, a shop owner who
lives in Luqiao, a suburban area of Taizhou in east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 Luqiao became an urban district of Taizhou. Lin and his
fellow rural villagers left their accustomed farmland and turn to
jobs in businesses or factories and workshops.
</P>
<P>
The change has required an increased awareness of such issues
as public safety, the environment and traffic, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
In Zhejiang rapid urbanization has increased the number of
towns in the province from more than 100 in the 1970s to 965.
</P>
<P>
The increased urbanization has resulted in behavioral problems
of adjusting to city life such as spitting, littering, vulgar
language and traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
"We are not only to build streets, mansions and large stores,"
said Wang Tingge, a Luqiao city official, "but also to set up an
orderly city management system and foster citizens with good
social morality."
</P>
<P>
The Luqiao government has begun the process of education,
issuing booklets to 35,000 families on social moral conduct and
encouraging citizens from 16 to 55 to study in the Civilized
Citizens' School. School subjects range from humanities to the
geography and history of Luqiao, legal trading to ethics and
etiquette, and sanitation to traffic regulations.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Communist Party members in the locality learn more
about political theories, party constitution, standard Chinese
pronunciation, English and computers.
</P>
<P>
Competition also thrives in Zhejiang in areas other than the
marketplace, Lin said. "We compete for which family can be elected
as the Family outstanding in socialist ethical and cultural
progress and which family has more members of higher education,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
