<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Weather Turmoil Before Yearend: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
assured top business leaders that the Philippines will definitely
overcome the speculative attacks against the peso before the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
"Given the market momentum, the peso will significantly
strengthen in the coming days," Ramos said in a keynote speech at
the 23rd Philippine Business Conference in Cebu City, the central
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 top businessmen attended the three-day meeting that
concluded today.
</P>
<P>
The peso, which has devaluated by 35 percent since the
financial turmoil swept Southeast Asia in early July, appreciated
substantially against the U.S. dollar on Thursday, rising to
34.852 pesos per dollar from Wednesday's 35.565 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he agreed with other leaders in the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) that speculative attacks caused
the fall of currencies and the slowdown of economies in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He added that ASEAN leaders have agreed to help each other in
addressing the financial storm, in which the Thai baht, Malaysian
ringgit, Indonesian rupiah and Singaporean dollar also plunged.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN also groups Brunei, Laos, Myanmar and Vietnam in addition
to the five nations.
</P>
<P>
In the same speech, Ramos also promised again that there will
be elections in 1998 as scheduled and that he will leave office
when his term ends on June 30, 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
