<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Traders Selling Farm Produce In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- some one million private
traders in central-south China's Hunan Province are now selling
fresh farm products not only locally but all across the country.
</P>
<P>
These traders already account for 95 percent of the aquatic
products sold, 80 percent of the vegetables, and 70 percent of the
fruit and pigs.
</P>
<P>
One rice market in Yiyang city near Dongting Lake has opened
270 rice processing factories that handle more than 100,000 tons
of rice annually that is bought from local farmers and sold all
over China.
</P>
<P>
Zhushan township in Anren county has become famous for
providing flowers and saplings and plants. The business is
expected to boost per capita annual income there to 4,000 yuan
(482 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
And, while baskets, shoulder poles, and handcarts were the main
means of transport in the past, traders now rely on motor
vehicles, trains and even aircraft, allowing them to ship fresh
fish and vegetables.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
