<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Apologizes to Canada Over Forged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 10 (Xinhua) -- In a move to amend the
damaged relations with Canada, Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy has apologized to Canada for the use of forged Canadian
passports by two Israeli agents in an attack on a Hamas leader.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported today that Levy sent a message to his
Canadian counterpart Lloyd Axworthy to offer the apology and
expressed the hope that this could ease the tension between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
A Canadian external affairs official is due to arrive in
Israel next week to discuss the current crisis. Levy called for
the return of Canadian Ambassador to Israel David Burger, who was
recalled by Ottawa last week to protest the use of forged
Canadian passports by the two agents in the failed assassination
attempt on Hamas leader Khaled Mashaal in Jordan last month.
</P>
<P>
The two Israeli agents attacking on Mashaal were arrested at
the scene by Jordanian police and later released under a
Jordanian-brokered bargain with Israel to exchange for the
release of Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin.
</P>
<P>
Canada was furious over the use of its passports in operations
against Islamic militants, saying this could lead to revenge
attacks against its citizens in the region.
</P>
<P>
Canada complained that it was not the first time that Israeli
agents used forged Canadian passports in operations. By
recalling its ambassador, the Canadian government demanded Israel
clarify the whole matter and promise to prevent such incidents
from occurring again.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Canada usually enjoy close relations, and there
has been good cooperation between security services of both
countries before the Mashaal affair. It was believed that it
would take time for both sides to amend the damaged relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Differ on Economic Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean government predicted
an optimistic economy but private economic research institutes are
raising strong doubts about the government's "too rosy" economic
outlook.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Korean Industries (FKI), representing the
interest of large businesses, even cautioned that the government's
forecasts would send a false signal on the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Three agencies - the state-run think-tank Korea Development
Institute (KDI), the Bank of Korea (BOK) and the Korea Institute
of Finance (KIF) - recently released their respective economic
predictions, all painting a bright picture of the national economy
for this year and the next.
</P>
<P>
KDI forecast that the nation's gross domestic product (GDP)
would grow 6.4 percent this year and 6.7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted that the nation's current-account deficit
would narrow to 7.9 billion U.S. dollars next year from this
year's expected shortfall of 13.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The think tank said that the sluggish national economy, which
started in the final quarter of 1995, already bottomed out in the
third quarter of this year and is in a recovery phase.
</P>
<P>
The KIF said that the nation's GDP would grow 6.3 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
The three agencies based their rosy predictions on an
expectation of strong exports, helped by the continued strength of
the U.S. dollar, a continuation of brisk exports and a rapid
recovery of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Most private economic research institutes, however, said the
nation's economic conditions will be less bright than those predicted
by government agencies.
</P>
<P>
Given the minus growth this September in letters of credit (LC)
arrivals for the nation's three major export items - automobiles,
semiconductors and steel products - they hold a gloomy outlook on the
nation's overseas shipments next year.
</P>
<P>
They also question the government's forecast of strong exports next
year, citing that predictions of a weak dollar next year would hamper
South Korean exports.
</P>
<P>
They cite an expected rise in capital equipment imports next year
by companies after two years of sluggish capital investments.
</P>
<P>
The FKI said that it feels the nation's GDP grew a mere 2
percent in the first half of this year, compared with the 5.9
percent growth the government announced.
</P>
<P>
"The 3.9 percentage-point gap between real GDP and the trade
terms-adjusted GDP is the biggest since 1990, when we started to
compile data on the difference," said Park Chan-ho, director of the
Economic Research Department of the FKI.
</P>
<P>
Park said that the wide gap was the result of aggravated
corporate profitability resulting from a drop in unit export
prices.
</P>
<P>
The FKI warned that the government's positive economic outlook,
based on export volumes, may be somewhat misleading.
</P>
<P>
"The national economy is actually suffering from a high jobless
rate, high insolvency rate and low corporate profitability," Park
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
