<HEADLINE> UNDP Urges to Eradicate Poverty Among Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Deputy resident representative
of United Nations Development Program (UNDP) Petra Lantz called
upon governments to embark on serious gender equality programs to
eradicate poverty among women.
</P>
<P>
She said Thursday that most of the people affected by poverty
were women, youth and other disadvantaged groups.
</P>
<P>
"Women and youth lack access to fundamentals of decent life
such as food, safe water, reliable health care, shelter and basic
education and governments should be seen to address these
problems," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said to reduce poverty governments should emphasize
economic growth and adopt policies aimed at improving the lives
of women.
</P>
<P>
There should be good governance and political empowerment of
women, she said, adding that women should have access to economic
and social assets such as land, training and access to credit.
</P>
<P>
"Over 1.3 billion people in the world still live on less than
one U.S. Dollar per day and the majority of them are women," she
said.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out human security and sustainable development
would only be realized if poverty was completely eradicated among
disadvantaged groups.
</P>
<P>
Poverty was no longer confined to the rural areas only but was
also growing very fast in urban areas, she said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP will mark the international day for the eradication
of poverty on October 17 in Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
