<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fertility Rate in Bangladesh Falls in Past 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The fertility rate in Bangladesh
declined by more than 50 percent over the last two decades with
the introduction of a home-visit system by Family Welfare
Assistants (FWA), FWA sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The rate in the country dropped to 3.3 children per woman of
childbearing age at present from 6.3 in 1975, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the home visit system by FWA contributed to
increasing the contraceptive prevalence rate to 49.2 percent from
7.7 percent in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The new approach has also helped change attitudes of women and
ensured wide participation in family planning approaches, the
sources added.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, there are more than 23,500 FWAs
working throughout the country and more than 10,000 additional
family planning field workers supported by non-government
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The home-visit program is now being implemented in 18
sub-districts in nine districts in the country involving more than
700,000 couples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
