<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Tamarisk Being Used To Prevent Sand Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- In Jiashi county in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, 450 farm families have
moved to 10,000 ha of sandy land that is being held in place by
tamarisk trees.
</P>
<P>
The region has vast stretches of sandy land in the world's
second largest desert area, the Taklimakan Desert in the Tarim
Basin.
</P>
<P>
The county has organized tens of thousands of laborers to plant
tamarisk seeds every year, and has been able to add 8,000 ha of
farmland by stopping the sand from drifting in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The region's Academy of Sciences began to study how to fight
desertification by using tamarisk in the early 1980s and found
that tamarisk can serve as a shelter against wind and sand and
also helps lower the groundwater level to improve saline-alkali
soil.
</P>
<P>
Counties like Jiashi that are on the edge of the desert have
planted some 100,000 ha in tamarisks in the past few years, and
have had good results. They plan to introduce the method to other
areas because of its low cost and effectiveness in dealing with
desertification.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Paintings with Western Flavor To Be Auctioned in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Western-influenced styles of
oil painting that were introduced into China a hundred years ago
will make their debut in a Shanghai auction.
</P>
<P>
The planners of Shanghai's Duoyunxuan autumn auction say they
plan to hold an oil painting auction in November.
</P>
<P>
In the 1920s and 30s, a group of Chinese oil painters like Xu
Beihong, Lin Fengmian, Wu Zuoren, Yan Wenliang and Zhou Bichu,
gained fame in Shanghai, the birthplace of the Chinese form of a
traditionally Western technique.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by both realism and impressionism, those painters
created unique cultural works for China.
</P>
<P>
The auction will include works of Xu Beihong, Zhou Bichu, Ding
Shaoguang, the Chinese-American Chen Yifei, and some by Pablo Picasso.
</P>
<P>
A touring exhibition is also scheduled for Beijing, Hong Kong
and Singapore in late October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
