<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Detains Kenyan Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A row has erupted between the
Kenyan authorities and a Somali strongman over three vehicles
hijacked by armed bandits in the past two weeks from eastern
Kenya's Garissa and Wajir districts bordering on Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Seyyid Hussein Abdalla, a resident at Somalia's Dobley border
town, several kilometers from the Kenyan border town of Liboi,
Garissa, has asked for a ransom of 250,000 Shillings before he
can release a Mercedes Benz truck to its Kenyan owner.
</P>
<P>
The truck, belonging to a Mombasa businessman, was hijacked by
militiamen at the Garissa-Dadaab road one week ago after
delivering food to the Dadaab refugee camp, according to local
reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two other vehicles together with an unspecified
number of cattle were also taken from border areas by armed
bandits.
</P>
<P>
These bandits were believed to be allies of Abdalla, who has
in the past been instrumental in the recovery of cattle and
vehicles taken from the Kenyan frontier districts, said the
reports.
</P>
<P>
However, Abdalla turned back a delegation of Kenyan officials
on releasing the vehicles and the cattle earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Garissa District Commissioner Ali
Mbwarali on the border, Abdalla said he would only release the
truck after the ransom money was paid to him.
</P>
<P>
"He denied knowledge of the two other vehicles and the
cattle,"a source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But Garissa police boss Alphonse Kalume said Abdalla should
know where the other vehicles and cattle were and Kenya would not
meet the Somali's ransom demand.
</P>
<P>
"We can't buy our truck twice," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
