<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Ready for Historical National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Three months after celebrating
Hong Kong's return to China and two weeks after the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China, Shanghai is again in the
festive spirits to welcome the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
From China's first street Nanjing Road to the narrow and dark
lanes, from the always-crowded Bund to the newly-built subway
platforms, colorful streamers and flashy lanterns decorated
everywhere in the financial hub of China, which is striving to
become an international finance and trade center.
</P>
<P>
The quadrennial games will raise its curtain here on Sunday,
with 13,000 athletes representing 45 delegations from China's
provinces, municipalities, autonomous regions, Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), the People's Liberation Army and
various professions.
</P>
<P>
"Being China's last national sports extravaganza of the
century, the Eighth National Games will demonstrate to the world
the country's social stability, the Chinese people's unity and
full confidence in the next century in the leadership of CPC with
Jiang Zemin as the core," Shanghai vice mayor Gong Xueping said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has spent 5.6 billion Yuans (about 700 million U.S.
dollars) in building stadiums and other sports facilities and
face-lifting the old ones.
</P>
<P>
The newly-built Shanghai "Barrel" Complex with a capacity of
80,000, which was festooned with colorful flags and banners, will
serve as the venue for the grand ceremony, bearing the theme of
Long Live The Motherland.
</P>
<P>
The complex, with an investment of 1.3 billion Yuans (about 170
million U.S. dollars), looks like a flying eagle from a birdview
and has become the symbol of the metropolitan.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot say it is the best in the world, but surely is one of
the toppest ones in the world," said Wu Shaozu, Minister of the
Chinese State Physical Culture and Sports Commission (SPCSC).
</P>
<P>
More historical colors will highlight the Games wherein HKSAR
will compete for the first time in the comprehensive sports meet
under the name of "Hong Kong, China" after China re-exercises its
sovereignty over the land on July 1.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR's Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa earlier encouraged the
Hong Kong athletes to win honors for HKSAR itself and their
motherland as well.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the National Games offered preferential rights to
Hong Kong athletes which allow them to skip the qualifying
tournaments for most of the individual sports.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 athletes will represent the HKSAR to compete in 22
sports in the two-week National Games.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in history, all non-Olympic sports but
China's traditional martial art (Wushu) are cancelled from the
National Games in order to attain more attention upon the Olympic
events.
</P>
<P>
Such an Olympic-oriented reform, as SPCSC Vice Minister Yuan
Weimin said, was believed to encourage Chinese athletes to achieve
better performance at the future Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
