<HEADLINE> Philippine Finance Chief Urges Regional Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo said today that he is in favor of the
regionalization of election for senators through charter changes.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo, an aspirant in next year's presidential election,
said a regional election for the senate would assure the people in
the southern Philippines of representation in laying down national
policies and laws.
</P>
<P>
"We have to face the fact that Mindanao needs people who will
speak on their behalf in the senate, carry on their ideals and
dreams of a progressive Mindanao. So far, they are being
represented by people who do not actually belong to them," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region of Muslim
Mindanao, warned earlier that they will boycott the 1998 national
elections if the constitution is not amended.
</P>
<P>
Misuari is also chairman of the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF) which signed a peace agreement last year to end a
24-year-old war with government troops.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF chief warned that his forces are even willing to "go
back to the hills" and wage war anew against the government if no
amendment to the constitution is made to allow a regional election
for senators.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo said any possible recurrence of disorder in Mindanao
would adversely affect the region's development and the country's
economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"We have already built up the confidence of the international
community about the ongoing peace development in Mindanao. At this
time, we cannot afford to disturb this process of transforming the
south into a rapidly growing economic zone in East Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the two sides laid down their arms, foreign investments
have kept coming to Mindanao, de Ocampo said, adding that the
government has just signed up 39 million U.S. dollars in loan
investments for the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
