<HEADLINE> China Not Yet Ponders On Another Bid for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- China has not seriously
considering the possibility to launch a second bid for the Olympic
Games, a top Chinese sports official said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shaozu, Minister of the State Physical Culture and Sports
Commission, said it demands careful and comprehensive
consideration for China to make another bid for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we have not seriously pondered upon that issue," Wu
said. "But as a member of the Olympic family, we will, as always,
take an active part in the Olympic movement and try hard to carry
forward the Olympic spirit."
</P>
<P>
It has been widely reported in Western media that either
Shanghai or Beijing might step in to bid for the 2008 Olympic
Games after Athens won the rights in September to host the 2004
Games.
</P>
<P>
Beijing narrowly lost its bidding war for the 2000 Games to
Sydney by two votes in 1993. "It was due to the non-sports
factors," Wu said of the reason why Beijing failed to bring home
the 2000 Olympic Games. 
