<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Have Floating Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will soon
have two prison ships anchored off the coast to house
awaiting-trial prisoners, local daily, the Citizen, reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Correctional Services Minister Sipo Mzimela was quoted as
saying that he expected his department would sign an agreement
next week with a private company, which would buy hulls from
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
"These hulls are originally built for floating hotels, but
that fell through. Now they are keen to sell, so the people who
buy them will get a very good price," Mzimela said.
</P>
<P>
The two ships would be used exclusively for awaiting-trial
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
There are about 35,000 awaiting-trial prisoners in South
Africa, judicial department officials said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which is in the period of transformation period,
has been troubled with increasing violence activities and crimes
for years.
</P>
<P>
Police authorities said that by the end of last year, there
were more than 124,000 inmates in South Africa's jails, which
were designed for about 97,000.
</P>
<P>
In addition to floating prisons, the Department of
Correctional Services is also thinking of turning disused mine
shafts into maximum security prisons to prevent prisoners
escaping from prison. At least 1,015 prisoners escaped from
prisons in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
