<HEADLINE> German World Cup Team Troubled by Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A number of German key players
were tamed by injuries before the team prepares for Saturday's
World Cup Group Nine qualifier against Albania.
</P>
<P>
Germany's already extensive injury list grew by two names on
Thursday when Mathias Sammer and Ulf Kirsten, the keystones of
coach Berti Vogts' offensive and defensive blocks, pulled out of
the match.
</P>
<P>
They became players the sixth and seventh players to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Schalke veteran Olaf Thon will be called up again to fill
Sammer's shoes.
</P>
<P>
Kirsten, who scored a hat-trick against Albania last time,
couldn't recover from a pulled hamstring and will watch from the
stands as he and injured captain Jurgen Klinsmann are replaced by
the unusual attack pairing of Oliver Bierhoff and Fredi Bobic.
</P>
<P>
"Our injury misery certainly is remarkable," said Vogts.
</P>
<P>
"Things have not been worse since I took on this job in
1990. Others complain when one or two players are hurt. But what
about the problems I have been struggling with since 1996?"
</P>
<P>
With all six nations in Group Nine playing their final games
Saturday, Germany are on top, two points ahead of Ukraine and
three in front of Portugal but with a vastly superior goal
difference over both.
</P>
<P>
Albania are bottom with only four points from nine games. A
draw would be enough for Germany to book a passage to the finals
next year in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
