<HEADLINE> Perkins's Last Hope for World Swimming Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The triple world record holder
and two-time Olympic champion Kieren Perkins over 1,500 meters
freestyle may fail to defend his title for next January's world
swimming champiosnhips as he finished only fourth in heats at
selection trials in Brisbane on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Only the top two swimmers are allowed to compete in individual
events at the championships in Perth next year. Unless Perkins
regains his form in Saturday's final, he will be thrown out of the
championships.
</P>
<P>
Perkins' heats time of 15 minutes 48.77 seconds was a far cry
from his own world record of 14:41.66 set in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Grant Hackett qualified fastest on Friday in 15:19.28 ahead of
Olympic silver medallist Daniel Kowalski and Jason Samuelson.
</P>
<P>
Perkins claimed he would switch his tactics in the final.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Perkins, who has failed to qualify for both the
200 and 400 meters freestyle this week, said he would aim at next
year's Commonwealth Games in Malaysia if he fails to qualify for
the world titles in Perth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
