<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Body Unveils Newest Asia-Pacific Forest Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund (WWF) for
nature study reveals that the Asia-Pacific region has already lost
88 percent of its original forest cover and only 5 percent of the
remaining forest area is currently protected.
</P>
<P>
The study also shows that within the next 25 years, only 10
percent of the Asia Pacific's original forest will be left, WWF
country representative Agus Purnomo said here Thursday when
launching the Asia Pacific forest map.
</P>
<P>
Of the 8.08 billion hectares of forests in the world 8,000
years ago, only 3.044 billion hectares remain today, according to
the forest map.
</P>
<P>
Tropical forests were being destroyed at a rate of 17 million
hectares a year, with similar losses in forest density across
Canada, Europe, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Asia lost the most compared to other regions," local press
today quoted Purnomo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new mapping project, developed by WWF in association with
the World Conservation Monitoring Center, studied forest cover and
forest protection in Africa, the Asia Pacific, Europe, Latin
America, North America and Russia to show the extent of forest
loss worldwide.
</P>
<P>
With Asia leading the way with its 88 percent forest loss,
Europe is not far behind with 62 percent. Africa has lost 45
percent of its forest cover, Latin America 41 percent, North
America 39 percent and Russia 35 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
