<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Parties Sign Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Warring factions on Papua
New Guinea's island of Bougainville signed a treaty in New Zealand
today, calling for a truce to the nine-year civil war on the
island.
</P>
<P>
The factions have been holding peace talks at the Burnham
military camp in the past 10 days near New Zealand's South Island
city of Christchurch, Television New Zealand reported.
</P>
<P>
The six-point treaty was signed by all the participants in the
talks, including representatives from the PNG government,
</P>
<P>
The treaty includes calls for an immediate stop to intimidation
 and to the armed conflict on Bougainville, for the promotion of
peace and reconciliation, for the setting up of a neutral group
to monitor the truce and for regular meetings by all parties to
review the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
The talks represented the second stage of a peace initiative
brokered by New Zealand. The warring factions met at the same
place in July and signed the "Burnham Declaration" in which they
expressed their desire for peace on the war-torn island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
