<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Poverty Efforts Working in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.5 million people in
Hainan province have risen above the poverty level during the past
nine years, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, when Hainan was separated from Guangdong Province to
become a new province, 2.02 million people were considered
poverty-stricken. A concerted effort by Hainan residents and
government officials has reduced that number to 450,000 with a
goal of eliminating poverty by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hainan, rich in tropical resources and arable land, has
established 212 agricultural production bases in its anti-poverty
drive. The province also has developed infrastructure facilities
in transportation, water supply, energy and housing.
</P>
<P>
In addition to building 992 kilometers of new roads and 1,100
kilometers of electric lines in rural areas, the provincial
government has earmarked a total of 15 million yuan annually for a
housing renovation project for ethnic minorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
