<HEADLINE> Trilateral Economic Summit To Be Held in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of India,
Bangladesh and Pakistan will jointly inaugurate on November 23
this year an economic development summit in Bangladesh's capital
Dhaka, visiting Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Industrialists of the sub-continent along with heads of
principal chambers of commerce would deliberate on promotion of
investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi foreign minister came here on Thursday evening
to deliver the official invitation to Indian Prime Minister I. K.
Gujral for the summit. He is expected to go to Pakistan later for
the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
The summit would be a unique event since the leading
industrialists of the sub-continent had never shared the same
platform to discuss economic development of the region, the
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The three prime ministers will be present to help the
industrialists to act in a meaningful way "as facilitators," Azad
explained.
</P>
<P>
The idea for an economic summit was proposed at the Male summit
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in
mid May this year.
</P>
<P>
SAARC embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, The Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina volunteered to host
the economic summit in Dhaka when the idea of development
initiatives at the private level was discussed by the prime
ministers of the three countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
