<HEADLINE> EC Eases Condition For Bangladeshi Garment Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC) has
accepted Bangladesh's plea for relaxed rule of origin to obtain
the General System Preference (GSP) for knitwear exports, thus
clearing ways for increased exports to Europe, the independent
United News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The acceptance came at a meeting of the Committee of the Rules
of Origin of the EC on Thursday in Brussels, the headquarters of
the EC, the UNB said.
</P>
<P>
The derogation will come into effect starting October 15 after
formal approval by all the 20 EC commissioners of the 15 European
Union (EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
"It's a great achievement for the country," Bangladeshi
Commerce Minister Tofael Ahmed was quoted as saying, "A
long-standing problem related to export of knit-garments to the
European countries has been resolved."
</P>
<P>
The minister said the relaxation of condition concerning the
origin of exports would help Bangladesh increase its knitwear
exports to the EU, Bangladesh's second-largest export market from
where the country earns over 75 percent of its export income from
knitted-garments.
</P>
<P>
The acceptance of the EC, which expressed its satisfaction over
the Bangladeshi government's bold steps in dealing with the GSP
problem, would help the country increase its export income to 10
billion dollars in five years, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
With this relaxation, Bangladesh's knitwear producers will be
able to export their products made of imported yarn, the UNB said.
</P>
<P>
The EC accepted the Bangladesh appeal after many rounds of
negotiation, persuasion and correspondence with the leaders of the
EC and the officials of the EU countries since January, the UNB
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
