<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Youth Less Athletic, Survey Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The physical strength and
athletic abilities of Japanese school students have continued to
decline, the local media reported.
</P>
<P>
An annual survey released by the Education Ministry Thursday
showed the physical strength of students between the ages of 10-19
has deteriorated in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Students scored lower on tests of running, jumping, throwing
and grip strength than students tested 10 years ago in primary
grades, middle and high schools, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide survey, conducted between May and October last
year, covered some 77,000 people of various ages, ranging from
primary students to people in their fifties.
</P>
<P>
Fifth- and sixth-year primary school students were tested on
their abilities in 13 activities that included jumping sideways
repeatedly, running 50 meters, and throwing handballs.
</P>
<P>
Middle-school students and those older were tested in 12
similar activities.
</P>
<P>
Overall scores for each activity have been gradually
deteriorating over the years, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1986, 18-year-old boys recorded lower scores in
all 12 activities, while both boys and girls in high schools
scored lower in most activities.
</P>
<P>
Changes in lifestyle that result in a lack of physical exercise
and increased study for entrance exams may be responsible for the
poor results of the survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Deputy PM Proposes to Postpone 18 Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Virabongsa Ramangkura has proposed to put 18 infrastructure
projects on hold as part of the efforts to cut down the
government's fiscal 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
The 18 long-term projects would need a combined investment in
excess of 424 billion baht (11.6 billion US dollars). They include
a subway system, expressways, a high-speed railway, a cargo
transport airline, auxiliary facilities for the new Bangkok
airport and an inter-city motorway.
</P>
<P>
Most of these projects were scheduled to start next year.
</P>
<P>
The government is under pressure to cut the 1998 budget to help
meet the conditions necessary for the use of the 17.2 billion US
dollar stand-by credit from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
If Virabongsa's suspension plan is approved by the cabinet, it
will help the government slash its 923 billion baht (25 billion
dollar) 1998 budget by another 120 billion baht (3.28 billion
dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
