<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Help Restore Confidence in Indonesia's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A team of International
Monetary Fund (IMF) officials will draw up measures aimed at
restoring confidence in Indonesia's economy and foreign exchange
market, World Bank country director Dennis de Tray said.
</P>
<P>
De Tray said here Thursday the team will arrive here this
weekend and will start work next Monday, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia is experiencing a confidence crisis rather
than a financial crisis, and that the IMF team will assess the
country's economic fundamentals and provide recommendations on
measures the government has to take to overcome the continued
weakening of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF can come in, they have facilities and staff and within
a matter of weeks, do an analysis, come up with the program, up
together the funding package and get it into place," he said.
</P>
<P>
De Tray insisted that Indonesia was not in a financial crisis
and it has between 20 billion and 25 billion U.S. dollars in
reserves to underpin reform programs.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said on Wednesday
that Indonesia was seeking long-term loans from international
financial institutions, including the IMF and the World Bank, to
help overcome the rupiah's sustained weakness.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has been depreciated by more than 33 percent in the
last three months and about 55 percent in this year alone. The
currency was badly hit compared to other currencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
Asked how much funding Indonesia might need, De Tray said there
had been no discussion of the level of funding, but stressed that
Indonesia was "not broken" and "not Thailand" and was just facing
a confidence crisis, not a financial crisis. Thailand got a 17.2
billion U.S. dollar bailout package put together by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State Minister/State Secretary Drs. Moerdiono said
Indonesia is not worried about conditions that would accompany
financial assistance from the International Monetary Fund and
other nations to bail it out of its financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"So far we've done our homework well. If we do our homework
well, there should be no conditions attached," he said.
</P>
<P>
But economists and analysts warned that financial assistance
from the IMF usually came with tough conditions attached to it and
Indonesia could have trouble in coping with them.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Muhammad said the IMF assistance was only a
"precautionary action." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0221 </DOCNO>
