<HEADLINE> CIS Countries Sign Documents on Fighting Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of safety and
intelligence institutions from the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) today held a meeting in Moldova's capital Kishinev
and signed a series of documents on jointly fighting crime, the
local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The documents include ensuring the safety of strategic
objectives within the CIS territory, an exchange of intelligence
about criminal groups and offenders, sabotage and long-term
programs on the development of cooperation in science and
technology, the Itar Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Nikolai Kovalev, director of the Russian Safety Bureau and CIS
chairman of the council of safety and intelligence leaders, said
the related CIS departments will join hands to fight against
terrorism, organized crime, drug trafficking, weapons smuggling
and sabotage by foreign intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that organized crimes have infiltrated various
fields of economic and social life and pose a threat to the whole
CIS as well as each of its member countries.
</P>
<P>
Kovalev pointed out that CIS safety and intelligence
institutions have achieved initial success in coordination and
cooperation in these aspects and have succeeded in capturing 1,500
tons of drugs through joint efforts in the last year.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia will share experience with other CIS countries
in fighting crime and provide the technology to help them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
