<HEADLINE> Four Countries to Buy Thai Rubber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Importers from Italy, Canada,
South Africa and Greece say they are prepared to buy rubber from
Thailand after comparing its quality against that of Malaysia and
Indonesia, according to Thailand's Rubber Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Today's press reports quoted Varaporn Kajornchaikoon, head of
the institute's research section, as saying that import
representatives from the four countries had arrived in Thailand
recently to study the institute's research and visit a rubber
testing laboratory.
</P>
<P>
She said they were impressed with the various measures in place
to control the quality of Thailand's rubber.
</P>
<P>
Some representatives said they would consider importing more
Thai rubber, while others who had not imported Thai rubber said
they would begin to do so.
</P>
<P>
Italy, which has highly advanced automobile industry, imports
Thai rubber worth 45 million U.S. dollars per year. Its annual
imports of Malaysian rubber are worth 75 million dollars, while
imports from Indonesia are worth 10 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Varaporn said South Africa was a potential market for many Thai
goods, especially rubber, as many car makers had located their
vehicle assembly plants there.
</P>
<P>
Canada and Greece had never bought Thai rubber but Varaporn
said both countries have expressed interest in buying smoked
rubber sheets and rubber locks from Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
