<HEADLINE> Iraq Offers Italy Preferential Trading Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 9 (Xinhua) -- After offering Italy a
"preferential trade role," Iraq today renewed its condemnation of
Britain and the United States for preventing the easing of the
embargo against the country, which was imposed after the Gulf War
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The decision to grant Italy the preferential status was
announced by Iraqi diplomat Al-Yacoubi in Rome at a press
conference on the eve of the United Nations' decision not to ease
the embargo, which is reviewed every six months.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat illustrated the "tragic situation" in his country
as a result of the devastating U.N. sanctions, and named Britain
and the United States as the main culprits in enforcing the
embargo.
</P>
<P>
"The British and U.S. representatives at the U.N. block
everything so that the end of the embargo moves further and
further into the distance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Yacoubi noted that though funds for the sale of Iraqi oil
under the U.N. Oil for Food resolution have reached the target
amount, only 20 percent has reached Iraq in the form of medicine
with the rest being blocked.
</P>
<P>
He said Italians are "deeply aware of the suffering of Iraqi
people," adding that relations between the two countries are
excellent, with visits to Baghdad by Italian commercial and
business delegations occurring frequently.
</P>
<P>
"One of many problems that occur is that when the Iraqi
government manages to reach an agreement with an Italian company,
delivery to Iraq is in fact prevented," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
