<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Improve Sri Lanka's Urban Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has granted technical assistance of 1.1 million US dollars
to help improve Sri Lanka's urban environment and uplift the
quality of life of urban residents, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The assistance is aimed at preparing a project that will help
government strengthen the urban development sector, provide low
income housing and facilitate urban land development.
</P>
<P>
About 27 percent of Sri Lanka's 18.5 million population live in
urban areas. Job opportunities and investment are mainly
concentrated in the capital city of Colombo, leaving small and
medium urban centers at a disadvantage, the Daily News said.
</P>
<P>
The government's goal is to provide essential service,
particularly for the poor, promote the growth of regions outside
Colombo and strengthen capabilities of local governments.
</P>
<P>
Urban infrastructure and services in Sri Lanka need to be
improved to promote the growth of small and medium urban centers.
</P>
<P>
The ADB assistance has two components, one dealing with the
urban development sector and the other with the low-income housing
and land management sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
