<HEADLINE> Chile, Peru Agree on Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chile and Peru have agreed to
eliminate customs tariffs on 2,000 products immediately after a
free trade agreement between the two countries becomes effective,
the Chilean Foreign Ministry announced today.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two countries held several rounds of
negotiations and discussed the possibility of signing a free trade
agreement before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The 2,000 products which will be exempt from customs duties are
those goods with lesser preferences in the Chilean-Peruvian
Partial Range Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The latest agreement did not include those goods on 10, 15 and
18 years of tariff exemptions, and those to be negotiated within
the next two weeks in Peru. 
</P>
