<HEADLINE> Foreign Referees to Debut in National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Foreign judges will make debut
in the Chinese National Games to rule water polo competition,
ending a 40-year history of Chinese-ruling-Chinese in the home
games, an official said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shouzhang, director of the competition department for the
eighth Games, failed to disclose the names and nationalities of
the two coaches, but stressed that the move was sure to ink a new
chapter in the history of the Games.
</P>
<P>
As water polo is far from a popular event in China, referees of
the sport are also limited in numbers in the country. "Such a
situation may provide an easy way for some referees to cheat in
favor of their native provincess," Wu added.
</P>
<P>
To nip in the bud such illegal rulings, Wu said, the Chinese
State Physical Culture and Sports Commission decided to take this
historical action by introducing foreign referees into the
national games.
</P>
<P>
"Our athletes have been training very hard for the quadrennial
games over the past four years," Wu said. "We must assure them of
an absolute arena of fair play."
</P>
<P>
The Eighth National Games, the last major sports gala held in
China in the century, will ring up its curtain on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
