<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Coffee Prices to Be Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The future
international prices for coffee will depend largely on the
harvests in main coffee producing countries, such as Brazil,
Indonesia, and the Central American nations, a Colombian expert
said today.
</P>
<P>
Cabriel Rosas Vega, president of Colombian Coffee Exporters
Association (Asoexport) said international coffee prices will
remain stable in the future, although exports of a few other
coffee-producing countries could modify projections.
</P>
<P>
Rosas Vega cautioned against the jump in output of countries
such as Mexico and Guatemala, which together have increased their
output by 2.4 million bags, each weighs 60 kilograms, in the last
two harvests.
</P>
<P>
Colombia reduced its production by 2.3 million bags in the same
period, going from 13 million to 10.7 million bags. The
preliminary forecasts of the Colombian harvest in the year 97-98
were 11.3 million bags.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, the world main coffee producer, has also shown a
recovery in production.
</P>
<P>
According to Rosas Vega, Brazil's projections for the 1997-1998
season is a harvest of approximately 28 million bags, although the
country has a capacity to produce 35 million bags.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the world coffee production has reached 103
million bags, with 75 million for export and 24 million going to
domestic consumption, Rosas Vega said.
</P>
<P>
The figures show a global consumption of 99 million bags,
indicating equilibrium and a relative stability in the prices.
</P>
<P>
But quotations will depend to a high degree on harvests in
Brazil, Indonesia, Vietnam, and Central America, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0245 </DOCNO>
