<HEADLINE> Cuban Communist Party Congress Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The fifth Cuban Communist Party
(PCC) congress, presided over by President Fidel Castro, resumed
working sessions today in Havana's Palace of Conventions.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Lage, member of the PCC Political Bureau, presented a
paper on economic resolutions that described the present economic
situation and the outlook for the country's financial potential.
</P>
<P>
The congress, which opened Wednesday, ends Friday. Castro
delivered a keynote address to the 1,500 delegates that lasted
nearly seven hours.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Castro, first secretary of the party, outlined
the difficulties facing his country since the disintegration of
the former Soviet Union in 1991. He also reviewed a series of
government policies aimed at keeping the economy going.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the continued U.S. economic embargo and the
hostility of the United States government toward his country.
</P>
<P>
A document titled "The Party of Unity, Democracy, and the Human
Rights We Defend" was approved on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The document had been discussed by 6.5 million citizens.
</P>
<P>
The congress will elect a new central committee, its first and
second secretaries and members of the Political Bureau. 
</P>
