<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Announces Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
announced his resignation this afternoon, bringing to an end his
17-month-old center-left government.
</P>
<P>
It came as a result of the Communist Refoundation Party's
refusal to soften its stance on rewriting the deficit-cutting
draft budget for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Unlike some of his predecessors, who tendered their
resignations after consulting the president, Prodi announced his
decision to quit before going to report his government's
difficulties to the president.
</P>
<P>
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro asked the Prodi government to
stay on in a caretaker capacity.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro, intent on avoiding a protracted political deadlock,
wasted no time in announcing immediate consultations with party
leaders, parliamentary speakers and former heads of state to try
and seek a new government formation and avert early elections
three and a half years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's government depended on the Communist Refoundation Party
in the lower house to pass legislation. But the communists refused
to back the deficit-cutting budget because of cuts amounting to 5
trillion lire (2.9 billion U.S. dollars) in pensions and welfare
spending.
</P>
<P>
The passing of the proposed budget is vital for Italy to become
a member of the European economic and monetary union.
</P>
<P>
The communist demands also include shortening the working week
from 40 hours to 30 hours and stimulating employment in the south,
where the unemployment rate is the highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Local media say the Prodi government has made great financial
and economic achievements since it took office in April 1996, and
it would take less time than before to resolve this government
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Fang Makes Miracle to Back to Tennis Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- To survive the injuries that
may ruin her career, Li Fang makes the miracle by backing to the
tennis court and regaining her prowess in her voyage towards the
pinnacle of the sport.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese woman tennis ace player has been winning flurry of
cheers when she was competing in the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident of keeping my title in the country and I'm on
the way to make the second attempt to surge into the top 50 in the
world," said Li Fang.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese woman made her professional debut in 1992 and
achieved her ever-best feat by ranking 49th in the world in 1995.
</P>
<P>
When all things went on her way to success, Li Fang was plunged
into the sea of sadness, all in a click of a second, as her tendon
was broken in her left knee in the early 1995.
</P>
<P>
Her doctors in Beijing recommended surgery twice and a whole
year rest for a full recovery, but Li Fang was in the eager mood
for competitions and returned to the court two months later by
choicing protective treatment instead.
</P>
<P>
But the injuries became worsen and hindered her movements since
then on before her knee totally betrayed her in March last year.
The Chinese player was thus kept away from the Centennial Olympic
Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The injuries charged her very expensive as she slipped away
from the top 100 and then top 200 last year.
</P>
<P>
In a dilemma of to-do-or-to-die, Li Fang hesitated no moment to
stake her career on a risky operation in a hospital in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
"I had no choice as the operation served as a lone springboard
for me to return to the court and to regain my prowess in the
sport," recalled Li Fang.
</P>
<P>
To break the old saying that misfortunes never come singly, the
lucky star beckoned upon the Chinese woman eventually, and smiles
crept upon her face as the surgery went into full success in last
October.
</P>
<P>
After an unbelievable short hiatus of five months, Li Fang
backed to the competition court in March and reapt four titles in
her 10 caps in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
In the Japanese Open last month, Li Fang bleezed past two
opponents, ranked in the top 70, and even stage tough challenges
against Vicario Arantxa Sanchez of Spain before bowing out of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
"Now, all the things went smoothly, even to my surprise. And I
may well be ahead of the 70th ranking should I have competed in
more meets," said Li Fang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
