<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- More than 120 people were killed Thursday by
Hurricane Pauline in Acapulco and other towns on Mexico's Pacific
Coast, said government sources.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- Intense artillery exchanges broke out Thursday
across the Congo River that separates cities of Kinshasa and
Brazzaville, Radio Cameroun reported.
</P>
<P>
Confusion spread through the streets of Kinshasa, capital of
the Democratic Republic of Congo, when it came under renewed
artillery and rocket attacks, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Two soldiers were killed and three others wounded when one
shell exploded at the gate of President Laurent Kabila's office.
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa responded by intensifying cannon and rocket fires
across the river, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisian President Zeinul Abidine Bin Ali today
reshuffled the government, with ministers of foreign and interior
affairs, among others, being replaced.
</P>
<P>
But no reason was given for the cabinet shake-up.
</P>
<P>
Saeed Bin Mustafa, currently Tunisia's Ambassador to Rome, was
appointed as the foreign minister, replacing Abderrahim Zouari,
according to Tunisian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The present Minister of Housing Ali Chaouch has been named as
the Minister of Interior to replace Mohamed Ben Rejeb.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Legislators from the 16 NATO member states and 15
central and eastern European countries gathered here Thursday to
discuss the future of the military alliance and new trans-Atlantic
relations.
</P>
<P>
Topics at the annual North Atlantic Assembly (NAA) session
included NATO in the next century, the costs of NATO enlargement,
the reform of the NATO military structure, trans-Atlantic trade in
relation to the defense industry, stability in the Balkans, the
status quo of the Russian armed forces and NATO partnership with
Romania.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also drew observers from Egypt, Japan, Sweden,
Canada, Austria and Switzerland, NAA Secretary General Simon Lunn
told the press Thursday.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) which is
enforcing blockade on Sierra Leone said Thursday it has destroyed
a gunship of the junta in retaliation of attacks.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ECOMOG headquarters in Monrovia,
capital of Liberia, said two of the junta's gunships on Wednesday
opened fire on ECOMOG positions in Lungi airport outside the
capital Freetown as well as innocent civilians taking refuge in
ECOMOG protection in the area.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- The Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) opened
its regular summit meeting Thursday to discuss economic
integration, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Prime ministers of the 12-member CIS reviewed a report
analyzing the economic situation and trend of the bloc at the
meeting held in Bishkek, capital of Kyrghyzstan.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the economic integration within the CIS is to
introduce an economic union between states, including the
setting-up of a tariff union and a payment union.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said Thursday that
he was going to submit his resignation to President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement after the end of a debate in the
Chamber of Deputies over the 17-month-old coalition's economic
policy.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's decision followed his failure to persuade the far-left
Refounded Communists to back the government's budget cuts.
