<HEADLINE> Beauty Salons booming in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Since China started its
reforms and opening up in the late '70s, the Chinese have become
more careful about their appearance and the people of northeast
China's Liaoning province are no exception.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 5,000 beauty parlors in the province, a
four-fold increase from five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Beauty parlors have now joined the ranks of major tertiary
businesses, along with restaurants and retail shops, according to
local officials. In order to increase and regulate the beauty shop
business, the provincial government has come up with a series of
laws and policies.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Trade Department was given the job of governing
the sector, and a provincial commission has been established to
examine and classify local beauty parlors.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many local beauty shops have gone from a
mom-and-pop business to modern enterprises, with some using a
computerized management system.
</P>
<P>
And, overseas investors have even entered the industry by
setting up joint ventures or wholly-owned beauty parlors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
