<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment in South China Port City Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, the capital of China's
island province of Hainan, has been using preferential policies to
improve its infrastructure facilities and is looking for
large-scale investment from home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to a local leading official, the city has made
efforts to develop energy, traffic, transportation,
telecommunications, and water supply sectors over the past decade,
and the efforts have now paid off.
</P>
<P>
The city has abundant power and water supplies, the official
says. The Haikou Power Plant has an installed capacity of 750,000
kw, ten times the figure of ten years ago, and the city's water
supply has a daily capacity of 559,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, it has built 388 km of roads, and the
Dongxian and Haikou-Yangpu expressways are now in operation.
</P>
<P>
Air service is also improving, with 50 air routes now available
and 500 flights connecting Hainan with inland provinces and
foreign countries. Another airport, Meilan International Airport,
is also being built. Haikou also has 70 cargo shipping routes to
ports in other parts of the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications sector has entered a new phase of
development with microwave and fiber optics technology, and
satellites. Telephones are available in 63 percent of Haikou's
homes, making it first of all provincial capitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
