<HEADLINE> Increasing Overseas Investment in South Chinese City's Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 10 (Xinhua) -- There has been more overseas
investment in industrial development in the capital of China's
island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
This can be attributed to an improved investment environment
and preferential policies for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the province has emphasized the development of
transportation, energy, and telecom sectors.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992-1996 period, the province got more than three
billion US dollars in overseas funds. A Sino-ROK (the Republic of
Korea) tin sheet plant, valued at 66 million US dollars, was built
in Haikou, with an annual production capacity of 100,000 tons of
thin tin-coated sheet as the first large industrial project in the
city.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-Singaporean brewery now has an annually production
capacity of 130,000 tons of "Tiger" beer, which has become a
popular brand name in the province.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, the province earned 34
million US dollars of foreign exchange from exports, a nearly 22
percent rise over the same period in 1996. A large number of
aquatic, electronic, and pharmaceutical products, garments, knit
gloves, and furniture have been shipped to Hong Kong, Japan, the
ROK, the US, and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
