<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Is Key To Narrowing China's East-West Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Market-oriented co-operation
has become a major means of correcting China's regional
inequalities, according to the State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Five autonomous regions and provinces in northwest China signed
agreements on 4,000 co-operation projects last year, with 13.5
billion yuan in investment.
</P>
<P>
"The West has changed its former practice of offering
preferential policies and tax rebates in co-operating with the
East and now is using the new method of exchanging its resources
and property rights through shares, stock, acquisitions,
purchases, and leases for the East's technology and capital," said
Zhou Baoheng, director of the Ningxia region's Economic and
Technological Co-operation Office.
</P>
<P>
The Northwest's GDP increased 9.8 percent in 1996, higher than
the national average, thanks to the co-operation.
</P>
<P>
An ailing carbon black company in Tianjin, in the north, has
become the country's largest enterprise of its kind, by buying
into three other businesses in central and western
provinces. Another example is Ningxia's Yinchuan Diesel Engine
Plant. The plant was practically bankrupt when it reorganized its
assets with a business in Jiangsu province in the east, and it now
produces more than 100 million yuan worth of added value goods.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest industrial center, has worked out
policies to encourage local enterprises to cooperate with the west
and will set aside 30 million yuan annually for the next three
years to develop markets, mainly in the west.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
