<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Bioengineering Crop to Raise Food Yields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Bioengineering crop could
increase food yields by up to 25 percent in the developing world,
where the population is growing while the cultivated land is
shrinking, said a report by a scientific panel convened by the
World Bank and the Consultative Group on International
Agricultural Research (CGIAR).
</P>
<P>
The report released today said that genes can be inserted into
the major food crops, including rice, corn, wheat, potatoes,
cassava and others to make them resistant to pests and diseases
without the need for chemicals, or make them resistant to drought,
cold, heat and other hostile conditions.
</P>
<P>
Genes can also be inserted to increase the food content of
crops, such as increasing the amount of starch in potatoes and
protein in rice, said the report "Bioengineering of Crop."
</P>
<P>
The scientists on the study stressed the urgency and importance
for the world to find new ways to increase food production as the
global population is growing by 3 billion over the next three
decades while the cultivated land has been shrinking rapidly.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the amount of cultivated land has decreased from
0.44 hectares per capita in 1961 to 0.26 hectares now and it is
expected to further decrease to 0.15 hectares by 2050 as a result
of increased population and erosion.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, increase in yields becomes a top priority in the
world and bioengineering provides one of the choices to meet the
demand, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
At the present stage, such research is conducted mainly in
industrial countries and progress has been made in some fields. In
the European Union, almost 2,000 biotechnology research projects
are underway, at least 1,300 of them using plants, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
In the developing countries, trials are conducted, of which
about 40 percent are for virus resistance, 25 percent for crops
modified herbicide resistance, and another 25 percent for insect
resistance, it added.
</P>
<P>
The group of scientists predicted that by the year 2000, annual
farm sales of biotechnology-derived products are likely to total
some 10 billion U.S. dollars, with 70 percent based on seeds and
30 percent on veterinary and other products.
</P>
<P>
However, some people fear that the new technology may produce
risks such as that the plants could be changed in unforeseen ways
that would not be known until it was too late to reverse the
process.
</P>
<P>
A group of scientists from the panel told news reporters today
that further studies are required, but there should be solutions
to any problems to come. The important thing at present was to
provide more support on the agricultural science in the developing
countries to increase their production of food.
</P>
<P>
They called for collaboration and cooperation between the
international institutions and the developing countries in the
field.
</P>
<P>
The panel particularly recommended the World Bank provide more
support to the scientific research and training of scientists in
biotechnology methods in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
It also asked the Bank to support an early warning system to
identify any troubles that arise and to introduce implements in
adapting new strains.
</P>
<P>
The panel suggested the World Bank increase its support of
research in biotechnology and related areas at international
agricultural research centers to ensure that the high-quality,
environmentally sustainable agricultural products and process are
developed and transferred to developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Asks Army to Find Chance to Test Laser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen has asked the Army to find chance to test the laser
against a satellite, although two resent tries were canceled
because of weather and technical reasons, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said, testers at the White Sands
Missile Range in New Mexico may still be able to conduct the
experiment.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen has asked Army officials to
keep looking for a chance to try out the laser, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, the testers have several chances to test the laser in
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
But the target spacecraft, an Air Force satellite, is dying as
its batteries are losing power. It needs sunlight to recharge its
batteries via solar panels, and is receiving less and less
sunlight as the earth tilts.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the test drew criticism from weapons
control experts who feared the experiment could lead to a space
weapons race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
