<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supporters of Campaign Finance Reform Vow to Fight Anew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Supporters of campaign
finance legislation promised to renew their efforts Thursday in
spite successive setbacks in the U.S. Senate this week.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator John McCain pledged to force a
straightforward vote on a leading overhaul bill he coauthored with
Democratic Senator Russell Feingold eventually, at least on a
stripped-down proposal to ban unregulated "soft money," if not on
the entire measure.
</P>
<P>
"We will not stop until we get the job done," said Senate
Democratic leader Tom Daschle at an appearance where he was joined
by House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt and other lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The McCain-Feingold measure remained deadlocked in the Senate
during the day, trapped between two competing filibusters. One,
mounted by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and majority
Republicans, is aimed at preventing a vote on the campaign finance
bill itself. It survived on a vote of 52-48, eight shy of the 60
needed to bring it to a close.
</P>
<P>
The second by Democrats, is designed to prevent Lott from
passing a provision that would require unions to get permission
from their members before spending dues money for political
purposes. That vote was 51-48.
</P>
<P>
The bill would prohibit "soft money," or unlimited, unregulated
donations from unions, corporations and others, to the two parties
for general activities in federal elections. It also would impose
new restrictions on outside groups that mount costly, independent
advertising campaigns within 60 days of an election, provide
incentives for politicians to hold down their personal
contributions to their own campaigns and provide for new
disclosure requirements on campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
The measure also would give non-union members the ability to
block unions from using payments in lieu of dues for political
purposes.
</P>
<P>
In the House, Gephardt threw his support behind an effort to
force Republican leadership to bring competing campaign finance
proposals to the floor before lawmakers adjourn for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
