<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mortgage Rates Hit 20-month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Mortgage interest rates in
the U.S. fell to the lowest level in nearly 20 months this week
but higher rates are expected in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
The average rate on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages declined to
7.26 percent from 7.31 percent a week earlier, the lowest level
since February 15, 1996, U.S. Freddie Mac, the mortgage company,
reported today.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. economists are predicting that mortgage rates will
drift up this year and probably next year but not drastically.
</P>
<P>
That's because bond market rates -- which serve as benchmarks
for mortgages -- bounced higher Wednesday after U.S. Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned investors of the risk of
higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts are predicting that the mortgage rate would
increase to 7.5 percent by the end of the year and perhaps 7.75
sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
Mortgage rates in the U.S. have fluctuated this year with
financial markets' nervousness about inflation. This year's peak
was 8.18 percent during the week ended April 3, after the Federal
Reserve tightened monetary policy on March 25.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,
averaged 6.82 percent this week, down from 6.87 percent and also
the lowest since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 5.49 percent, down from 5.52 percent and
the lowest in 10 weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
