<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weizman Urges U.S. to Play Decisive Role in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer
Weizman on Thursday urged the United States to play a definite and
decisive part in revitalizing Israeli-Palestinian partnership so
that the stalled Middle East peace process could be pulled back on
track.
</P>
<P>
"I do think the United States has to be more definite and
decisive about the issue," Weizman told an audience at the
National Press Club at the end of a five-day visit to Washington.
"Definitely, the (U.S.) president has a role to play. Without
America we will not clinch deals."
</P>
<P>
Weizman cited U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright as
having said during a visit to Israel last month that the United
States considered the Middle East an area of vital importance. and
she also described the United States as a "full partner" in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Now, I ask you logically, if the area is an area of vital
importance... and you are a full partner, and two partners don't
get together, does a third party sit back and see the partnership
wither away?" Weizman said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, who is from the Labor Party and has challenged Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's tough line, told the audience that
included Arab diplomats: "We are destined to live together."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971010.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Edge Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks finished mostly
lower today with the Dow Jones industrial average fell 33.64 to
8,061.42.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 549.74 million
shares as against 572.27 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 3.22 to 970.62, and
the NYSE composite index fell 1.41 to 508.16.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 4.08 to 1,745.85, its sixth
consecutive record close.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 rose 0.89 to 464.55, easily erasing
Wednesday's minuscule loss of 0.12 and pushing back into record
terrain.
</P>
<P>
But the American Stock Exchange composite index, which is
dominated by smaller companies, slipped 1.08 to 717.22, its second
straight decline after running seven record highs on end.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates shot higher again in the bond market after
hitting a 19-month low on Tuesday. The yield on the 30-year
Treasury rose as high as 6.46 percent before easing to 6.35
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
